kay sa Modyul \\r\\n\\r\\n3. Panonood ng Pelikulang Hinggil sa Isyung Pangkultura\\r\\n\\r\\n4. Pagsuri ng pelikulang pinanood\\r\\n\\r\\n5. Pagbibigay ng pananaw tungkol sa aralin.\\r\\n OFF-SITE: 1. Pagbabahagi ng karanasan  tungkol sa panonood ng Pelikulang Pilipino\\r\\n\\r\\n2. Virtual na pagtuturo (PowerPoint Presentation)\\r\\n\\r\\n3. Panonood ng Video sa Learning Management System (LMS) ng pagtatalakay (Linggo 17)\\r\\n\\r\\n,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nOn-site:\\r\\n- Learning Plan\\r\\n- Workbook\\r\\n- Internet Sources\\r\\n\\r\\nOff-site:\\r\\n- Learning \\r\\n  Management \\r\\n  System\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n,, Output Materials:\\r\\nOn-site:\\r\\n- Workbook Answer \\r\\n   (Compiled in \\r\\n   portfolio)\\r\\n- Project-\\r\\n  based: Digital \\r\\n  Scrapbook (Rubric)\\r\\n- Quiz Result\\r\\n- Notes\\r\\n- Assignment\\r\\n\\r\\nOff-site:\\r\\n- Pagsama samahin ang lahat ng na-download na materyales mula sa Learning Management System (LMS) para isama sa iyong subject portfolio.\",\"Week 18\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nFinal Exam\"}',NULL,3,NULL,NULL,'Ang SINESOS ay kurso sa Panitikan na nakatuon sa paglinang sa kasanayan sa kritikal na panonood at komparatibong pagsusuri ng mga pelikulang makabuluhan sa konteksto ng Pilipinas. Sa pamamagitan\r\nng dulog na tematiko ay inaasahang masasaklaw ng kurso ang mga paksang makabuluhan sa pag-unawa ng kontemporaryong lipunang lokal, nasyonal at internasyonal, alinsunod sa pagtanaw sa panitikan bilang\r\ntranspormatibong pwersa.','[{\"pilo\":\"Ang SINESOS ay kurso sa Panitikan na nakatuon sa paglinang sa kasanayan sa kritikal na panonood at komparatibong pagsusuri ng mga pelikulang makabuluhan sa konteksto ng Pilipinas. Sa pamamagitan ng dulog na tematiko ay inaasahang masasaklaw ng kurso ang mga paksang makabuluhan sa pag-unawa ng kontemporaryong lipunang lokal, nasyonal at internasyonal, alinsunod sa pagtanaw sa panitikan bilang transpormatibong pwersa.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"pilo\":\"Makapagpamalas ng mahusay at mabisang komunikasyon (pagsulat, pagsasalita, at paggamit ng bagong teknolohiya)\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"pilo\":\"Makagamit ng batayang konseptong batay sa mga dominyo (domain) ng kaalaman\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"pilo\":\"Maunawaan ang kompleksidad ng kalagayan ng sangkatauhan\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"Maipaliwanag ang karanasan ng sangkatauhan sa iba\\u2019t ibang perspektiba\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"Masuri ang kasalukuyang sitwasyon ng mundo sa pamamagitan ng\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"Epektibong makagampan sa gawain bilang isang pangkat\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"pilo\":\"Makagamit ng mga kasangkapan gaya ng kompyuter upang epektibong makapagproseso ng impormasyon\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"pilo\":\"Makagamit ng bagong teknolohiya na tutulong at magpapadali sa pagkatuto at pananaliksik\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"P\"}]','[{\"cilo\":\"Maipaliwanag ang piling teorya sa pagsusuri ng pelikulang panlipunan.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"cilo\":\"Matukoy ang mga pelikulang panlipunan na makabuluhan sa kontekstong Pilipino.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"cilo\":\"Magamit ang wikang Filipino sa pagsulat ng komparatibong pagsusuri ng pelikulang panlipunan.\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Makapagpahayag ng mga makabuluhang kaisipan hinggil sa kabuluhan sa lipunan ng mga paksang pelikula.\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Mapanuring maisakatuparan ang makrokasanayang panonood.\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Mapalalim ang pagpapahalaga sa mga positibong aspekto ng kultura ng mga mamamayan sa iba\\u2019t ibang panig ng mundo.\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"cilo\":\"Malinang ang adhikaing makapag-ambag sa pagbabagong panlipunan.\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"cilo\":\"Makapag-ambag sa pagtataguyod ng wikang Filipino bilang daluyan ng makabuluhan at mataas na antas ng diskursong pangkultura, pampanitikan, at  pampelikula.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"L\"}]','1. Masusing makapagsuri ng “mga teksto” (nakasulat, biswal, pasalita atbp.)\r\n2. Makapagpamalas ng mahusay at mabisang komunikasyon (pagsulat, pagsasalita, at paggamit ng bagong\r\nteknolohiya)\r\n3. Makagamit ng batayang konseptong batay sa mga dominyo (domain) ng kaalaman\r\n4. Maunawaan ang kompleksidad ng kalagayan ng sangkatauhan\r\n5. Maipaliwanag ang karanasan ng sangkatauhan sa iba’t ibang perspektiba\r\n6. Masuri ang kasalukuyang sitwasyon ng mundo sa pamamagitan ng\r\n7. Epektibong makagampan sa gawain bilang isang pangkat\r\n8. Makagamit ng mga kasangkapan gaya ng kompyuter upang epektibong makapagproseso ng impormasyon\r\n9. Makagamit ng bagong teknolohiya na tutulong at magpapadali sa pagkatuto at pananaliksik','Sa pagtatapos ng kurso, inaaasahang matututuhan ng mga mag-aaral ang mga sumusunod:\r\nKaalaman\r\n1. Maipaliwanag ang piling teorya sa pagsusuri ng pelikulang panlipunan.\r\n2. Matukoy ang mga pelikulang panlipunan na makabuluhan sa kontekstong Pilipino.\r\nKasanayan\r\n1. Magamit ang wikang Filipino sa pagsulat ng komparatibong pagsusuri ng pelikulang panlipunan.\r\n2. Makapagpahayag ng mga makabuluhang kaisipan hinggil sa kabuluhan sa lipunan ng mga paksang pelikula.\r\n3. Mapanuring maisakatuparan ang makrokasanayang panonood.\r\nKahalagahan\r\n1. Mapalalim ang pagpapahalaga sa mga positibong aspekto ng kultura ng mga mamamayan sa iba’t ibang panig ng mundo.\r\n2. Malinang ang adhikaing makapag-ambag sa pagbabagong panlipunan.\r\n3. Makapag-ambag sa pagtataguyod ng wikang Filipino bilang daluyan ng makabuluhan at mataas na antas ng diskursong pangkultura, pampanitikan, at pampelikula.','At the end of the course, students should be able to:\r\n1. evaluate primary sources for their credibility, authenticity, and provenance\r\n2. analyze the context, content, and perspective of different kinds of primary sources\r\n3. determine the contribution of different kinds of primary sources in understanding Philippine history\r\n4. develop critical and analytical skills with exposure to primary sources\r\n5. demonstrate the ability to use primary sources to argue in favor or against a particular issue\r\n6. effectively communicate, using various techniques and genres, their historical analysis of a particular event or issue that could help others understand the\r\nchosen topic\r\n7. propose recommendations/solutions to present-day problems based on their understanding of root causes and their anticipation of future scenarios\r\n8. display the ability to work in a term and contribute to a group project\r\n9. manifest interest in local history and concern in promoting and preserving our country’s national patrimony and cultural heritage','San Juan, D.M., et.al. (2017). CHED memo. No. 57, series of 2017 at mga silabus sa Filipino sa kolehiyo.\r\n\r\nSan Juan, D.M., Sinesosyedad','Websites:\r\nXmovies8.tv\r\nGomovies.to\r\nWatchmovies.info\r\nPinoyweekly.org\r\nFacebook.com/pinoyweekly.org\r\nManilatoday.net\r\nfacebook.com/tudlaproductions\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/user/tudlaproductions\r\nfacebook.com/altermidya\r\ncrossingconnection.com\r\nwww.plarideljournal.org','1. Participation and Attendance at least 80%\r\n1.1 Student must complete at least 80% active participation in class discussions, weekly accounting exercises, quizzes and group activities.\r\n1.2 Student must have a punctual attendance according to his/her class schedule.\r\n\r\n2. Course Project/Final Output\r\n2.1 Student must be able to submit a final project/portfolio. These include compilation of workbook activities, and submission of printed or digital output such as video presentation, slide presentation, and scrapbook.','Cluster Leader: \r\nDR. TIMOTEO P. ORIJUELA\r\n\r\nCluster Members:','Faculty Member:\r\nDR. TIMOTEO P. ORIJUELA\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConsultation Hours:\r\n\r\nTime and Venue: Monday: 1:30-2:30 \r\nWednesday: 12:30-2:30 \r\nMV Campus – BSCPE Program\r\nOffice of the Program Head','GELYN T. BANAL, LPT','MICHAEL L. BERSAMIN, LPT','CHARLIE I. CARIÑO, Ph.D','2026-02-06 16:55:37','2026-02-06 16:55:37',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
(42,'NSTP 2','NATIONAL SERVICE TRAINING  PROGRAM 2','Minor','NSTP 2','CHED',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'{\"Week 0\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nBCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives, Philosophy and School Organizational Structure School Policies Orientation in Online and Modular Learning System,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nRecite, internalize and explain the BCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives and Philosophy\\r\\nDeepen knowledge on the school\'s policies, guidelines, rules and regulations.\\r\\nFamiliarize on the new normal system of education through online, modular learning system and Blended Learning Delivery Modality (BLDM),, Assessment: ONSITE: Identify the Vision and Mission statements of BCP.\\r\\nCritically analyze these statements in 500 words, focusing on the following:\\r\\nThe clarity and coherence of the statements.\\r\\nHow these statements reflect the school\'s commitment to education.\\r\\nThe alignment of these statements with the current educational landscape.\\r\\nVerify that the BCP VMGO are align with the school goals thru checklist (PMED tools) OFFSITE: Navigate LMS and know the function of each feature.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Read and internalize the following printed materials for Students and Parents Orientation: OFF-SITE: Presentation and Lecture Discussion (PowerPoint Presentation) of Students and Parents Orientation:,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nInstructional Materials\\r\\nVideo Presentation of BCP Hymn\\r\\nYouTube Video Title: BESTLINK COLLEGE OF THE PHILIPPINES HYMN (BCP hymn)\\r\\nhttps:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=NuEYO11Wb4E\\r\\nStudent Hand Book\\r\\nLearning Management System,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCheck alignment report\",\"Week 1\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nCourse Orientation, Review of NSTP Law and CWTS 1 Principles, Introduction to Community Immersion for CWTS 2,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nArticulate the course objectives and expectations for NSTP 2 (CWTS 2); Recall fundamental principles of the NSTP Law and Civic Welfare Training Service; Explain the significance of community immersion in nation-building.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Active participation in Q&A during orientation; Group sharing of CWTS 1 key takeaways. OFFSITE: Read and annotate the NSTP Law (RA 9163) provisions relevant to CWTS; Write a brief reflection on personal expectations for NSTP 2.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive lecture-discussion on the syllabus and course policies; Open forum for clarifications; Group brainstorming on the importance of civic engagement. OFF-SITE: Access and review course syllabus and CHED Memorandums on NSTP via LMS; Watch an introductory video on community development principles.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nNSTP Law (RA 9163) copy; Course Syllabus; CHED Memorandums on NSTP; Projector and presentation slides; Online video resource (e.g., \'Introduction to Community Development\').,, Output Materials:\\r\\nSigned Course Expectation Sheet; Reflection Paper on NSTP 2 expectations.\",\"Week 2\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nCommunity Needs Assessment: Methods, Tools, and Situational Analysis,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nApply various methods and tools for comprehensive community needs assessment; Identify priority community issues and potential areas for intervention; Analyze existing community profiles and socio-economic data.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group workshop on designing a simple community survey questionnaire; Oral presentation of preliminary findings from a given case study. OFFSITE: Research and compile examples of successful community needs assessment reports; Conduct an online situational analysis of a chosen local community (e.g., using publicly available data).,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on participatory rural appraisal (PRA) techniques and rapid rural appraisal (RRA); Group discussion on ethical considerations in data gathering; Workshop on SWOT analysis for community assessment. OFF-SITE: Online reading on different data gathering techniques (e.g., KII, FGDs); Watch video tutorials on using digital tools for data collection (e.g., Google Forms, KoboToolbox).,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nNeeds assessment guidebooks; Sample survey questionnaires and interview protocols; Case studies of community assessments; Projector and presentation slides; Access to Google Forms\\/KoboToolbox tutorials.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft Community Needs Assessment Plan; Initial Community Profile Outline.\",\"Week 3\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nProject Planning and Development: Problem Identification and Goal Setting,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nFormulate clear, concise, and verifiable problem statements for community issues; Develop SMART (Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound) goals and objectives for community projects; Justify the relevance and necessity of proposed interventions.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group activity: Problem Tree Analysis for a selected community issue; Presentation of draft problem statements and objectives. OFFSITE: Refine problem statements and objectives based on peer feedback; Research best practices in community project goal setting.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive lecture on logic model and project cycle management; Facilitated group discussion on transforming identified needs into actionable project goals; Brainstorming session on innovative solutions. OFF-SITE: Online reading on project planning methodologies (e.g., Logical Framework Approach); Virtual collaboration on shared documents for project goal formulation.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nProject planning templates (e.g., Logframe Matrix); Case studies of successful community projects; Whiteboard\\/flip chart; Online collaboration tools (e.g., Google Docs).,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft Problem Statement and Project Goals & Objectives.\",\"Week 4\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nProject Planning and Development: Strategy Formulation and Resource Mobilization,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nDesign effective and sustainable project strategies and activities; Identify and map potential human, financial, and material resources; Develop strategies for stakeholder engagement and partnership building.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group workshop: Activity planning and sequencing using a Gantt chart template; Role-play: Approaching potential community partners. OFFSITE: Develop a preliminary resource mobilization plan for their proposed project; Identify potential local organizations or government units for collaboration.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on sustainable development goals (SDGs) and their relevance to community projects; Group discussion on ethical resource mobilization; Mentored project strategy development. OFF-SITE: Online research on local government programs and NGO initiatives related to their project theme; Watch webinars or videos on effective partnership building.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nProject activity templates; Resource mapping tools; Sample MOUs\\/Partnership agreements; SDGs framework document; Projector and presentation slides.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDetailed Project Activities and Resource Mobilization Plan.\",\"Week 5\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nProject Proposal Writing and Presentation,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nConstruct a comprehensive and well-structured community project proposal; Effectively present the project proposal to a panel, articulating its rationale, methodology, and expected outcomes; Integrate feedback for proposal refinement.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group presentation of the initial project proposal (mock defense); Peer critique session. OFFSITE: Prepare a full draft of the Community Project Proposal; Develop presentation slides and visual aids.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on the components of a robust project proposal (e.g., Introduction, Rationale, Methodology, Budget, M&E Plan); Workshop on public speaking and presentation techniques; Faculty consultation for proposal review. OFF-SITE: Online submission of draft proposal for initial feedback; Access to online resources on effective proposal writing and presentation skills.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nProject proposal guidelines and rubric; Sample successful project proposals; Presentation software (e.g., PowerPoint, Google Slides); Projector; Whiteboard.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft Community Project Proposal (Full); Presentation Slides.\",\"Week 6\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nPrelim Exam\",\"Week 7\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nProject Implementation Strategies and Management,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nOutline key steps for effective project implementation; Utilize basic project management tools to organize and track project activities; Define roles and responsibilities within the project team.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group activity: Development of a detailed work breakdown structure (WBS) for their project; Role-playing project team coordination scenarios. OFFSITE: Research on best practices for managing community-based projects; Create a communication plan for their project team and community partners.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive lecture on project management principles (e.g., Gantt charts, PERT charts); Discussion on risk management in community projects; Team-building activities for project cohesion. OFF-SITE: Online tutorials on project management software (e.g., Trello, Asana - basic features); Reading articles on leadership and teamwork in community development.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nProject management templates (e.g., Gantt chart, WBS); Case studies on project implementation challenges; Projector and presentation slides; Access to online project management tools.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDetailed Project Work Plan with assigned roles; Draft Communication Plan.\",\"Week 8\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nCommunity Immersion Protocol and Safety Guidelines,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nAdhere to ethical guidelines and cultural sensitivities during community immersion; Apply safety protocols and emergency preparedness measures in the field; Demonstrate responsible and respectful engagement with community members.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Scenario analysis: Ethical dilemmas in community work; Basic first aid demonstration and practice (if applicable). OFFSITE: Review and sign a community immersion ethics and safety waiver; Research local customs and traditions of their target community.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on CHED guidelines for community immersion; Discussion on cultural competence and sensitivity; Guest speaker from a local emergency response unit (e.g., Red Cross, MDRRMO) on safety and first aid. OFF-SITE: Online modules on cultural awareness and sensitivity; Watch videos on basic first aid and emergency response; Review institutional guidelines for off-campus activities.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nCHED Memorandums on NSTP community immersion; Institutional ethics and safety guidelines; First aid manual; Emergency contact list template; Projector and presentation slides.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nSigned Community Immersion Ethics and Safety Waiver; Personal Safety and Emergency Contact Card.\",\"Week 9\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMidterm Assessment: Project Proposal Defense and Refinement,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nFormally defend the refined community project proposal to a panel of evaluators; Respond effectively to questions and feedback regarding the project\'s feasibility, impact, and sustainability; Integrate feedback to finalize the project plan.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Formal Project Proposal Defense (oral presentation with Q&A); Peer and faculty critique session. OFFSITE: Revise the project proposal based on feedback received during the defense; Prepare for the actual project implementation phase.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Panel defense with faculty and possibly external evaluators; Constructive feedback session; One-on-one consultation with faculty for final adjustments. OFF-SITE: Online submission of revised project proposal; Virtual team meetings for final planning and task delegation.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nProject Proposal Defense Rubric; Feedback forms; Projector; Whiteboard; Video conferencing tools for remote evaluators (if applicable).,, Output Materials:\\r\\nFinalized Community Project Proposal (incorporating all revisions); Project Defense Feedback Form.\",\"Week 10\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMonitoring and Evaluation (M&E) for Community Projects (Part 1),, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nExplain the importance and principles of monitoring and evaluation in community development; Differentiate between process and outcome indicators; Develop relevant and measurable indicators for project success.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group activity: Developing SMART indicators for their project\'s goals and objectives; Discussion on baseline data collection methods. OFFSITE: Research on different M&E frameworks applicable to community projects; Identify existing data sources for baseline information in their target community.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on the basics of M&E, including logical framework approach (LFA) and theory of change; Case study analysis of M&E in successful community projects; Workshop on designing simple monitoring tools. OFF-SITE: Online reading on M&E terminology and concepts; Watch videos explaining the difference between monitoring and evaluation.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nM&E handbooks and guidelines; Sample indicator frameworks; Case studies on project evaluation; Projector and presentation slides.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft M&E Plan with identified indicators and baseline data sources.\",\"Week 11\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMonitoring and Evaluation (M&E) for Community Projects (Part 2),, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nDesign simple data collection tools for monitoring project progress; Apply basic data analysis techniques to interpret project data; Develop effective reporting mechanisms for stakeholders.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group workshop: Designing a project monitoring logbook and simple observation checklist; Practice interpreting mock project data. OFFSITE: Refine data collection tools for their specific project; Prepare a schedule for data collection during project implementation.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive lecture on qualitative and quantitative data collection methods; Hands-on workshop using spreadsheet software for basic data tabulation; Discussion on feedback loops and adaptive management. OFF-SITE: Online tutorials on using spreadsheet software (e.g., Excel, Google Sheets) for data entry and basic analysis; Research on ethical data handling and privacy in community settings.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nSample monitoring forms and logbooks; Basic spreadsheet software (e.g., Microsoft Excel, Google Sheets); Projector and presentation slides; Data privacy guidelines.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDeveloped Data Collection Tools (e.g., Logbook, Checklist, Survey Form); Initial Data Analysis Plan.\",\"Week 12\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMidterm Exam\",\"Week 13\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nProject Documentation and Reporting,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nPrepare comprehensive and accurate project documentation throughout the implementation phase; Write clear, concise, and impactful progress and terminal reports; Utilize various media for effective reporting to different stakeholders.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group activity: Drafting a progress report based on mock project data; Peer review of draft reports. OFFSITE: Compile all project documentation (photos, attendance sheets, meeting minutes, etc.); Begin drafting the final project report.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on the importance of systematic documentation and different types of project reports; Workshop on effective report writing, including executive summaries and recommendations; Discussion on ethical reporting and data visualization. OFF-SITE: Online reading on technical writing and report structuring; Access to templates for progress and terminal reports; Tutorials on creating infographics or visual summaries.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nSample progress and terminal reports; Report writing guidelines; Project documentation templates; Projector and presentation slides; Graphic design tools (e.g., Canva - basic).,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft Progress Report; Comprehensive Project Documentation Portfolio (digital).\",\"Week 14\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nSustainability and Exit Strategies for Community Projects,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nDevelop strategies to ensure the long-term sustainability of community projects; Formulate effective exit strategies that promote community ownership and continuity; Analyze factors contributing to project success and failure in terms of sustainability.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Case study analysis of sustainable vs. unsustainable community projects; Group discussion on mechanisms for community ownership. OFFSITE: Research on local government policies or community structures that can support project continuity; Outline a preliminary sustainability and exit plan for their project.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive lecture on principles of sustainable community development; Brainstorming session on capacity building and local leadership development; Discussion on scaling up and replication of successful initiatives. OFF-SITE: Online reading on best practices for project sustainability and exit planning; Watch documentaries or interviews with community leaders on maintaining project impact.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nFrameworks for project sustainability (e.g., institutional, financial, environmental); Case studies of successful project handovers; Projector and presentation slides.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft Sustainability and Exit Plan for their Community Project.\",\"Week 15\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvocacy and Social Marketing for Community Development,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nFormulate compelling advocacy messages for community issues; Apply social marketing principles to promote civic awareness and participation; Utilize digital platforms for broader dissemination of community development initiatives.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group workshop: Designing a mini-advocacy campaign (e.g., poster, slogan, short video concept); Presentation of advocacy materials. OFFSITE: Develop a draft social media content plan for their project\'s advocacy; Research on ethical considerations in digital advocacy.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on the principles of advocacy, lobbying, and social marketing; Discussion on effective communication strategies for different audiences; Workshop on storytelling for social change. OFF-SITE: Online research on successful advocacy campaigns and social marketing initiatives; Tutorials on creating engaging content for social media (e.g., short videos, infographics).,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nSocial marketing frameworks; Case studies of advocacy campaigns; Digital content creation tools (e.g., Canva, CapCut - basic); Projector and presentation slides.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nDraft Advocacy Plan or Social Media Campaign for their Project.\",\"Week 16\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nFinal Project Presentation and Evaluation,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nPresent the implemented community project\'s outcomes, challenges, and lessons learned comprehensively; Critically evaluate the project\'s overall effectiveness and impact against its objectives; Articulate personal and group growth derived from the immersion experience.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Final Project Presentation (oral presentation with visual aids, Q&A); Panel evaluation by faculty and community representatives (if applicable). OFFSITE: Finalize the Project Terminal Report; Prepare for the comprehensive final project presentation.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Project showcase\\/symposium; Panel evaluation and feedback; Peer evaluation of project presentations. OFF-SITE: Online submission of the Final Project Terminal Report; Recording of practice presentations for self-assessment.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nFinal Project Presentation Rubric; Project Terminal Report template; Projector and presentation slides; Video recording equipment (optional).,, Output Materials:\\r\\nFinal Project Terminal Report; Final Project Presentation (oral and digital materials).\",\"Week 17\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nPost-Project Reflection and Future Engagements,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nArticulate personal and group learning, insights, and challenges encountered throughout the CWTS 2 experience; Identify opportunities for continued civic engagement and personal development; Formulate a personal action plan for sustained community involvement.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Individual and group sharing of reflections; Open forum on future civic engagement opportunities. OFFSITE: Write a comprehensive individual reflection paper on the entire NSTP 2 (CWTS 2) experience; Develop a personal action plan for future civic engagement.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Guided reflection session (e.g., \'What went well, what could be improved, what was learned\'); Discussion on pathways for continued community service (e.g., volunteer organizations, social entrepreneurship); Mentoring session on career and civic engagement. OFF-SITE: Online submission of reflection paper and action plan; Access to resources on volunteerism and social causes.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nReflection prompts; Handouts on volunteer organizations; Projector and presentation slides; Online journal platforms.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nComprehensive Individual Reflection Paper; Personal Action Plan for Civic Engagement.\",\"Week 18\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nFinal Exam\"}',NULL,3,NULL,NULL,'Civic Welfare Training Service (CWTS2) is a sequel to CWTS1. It is designed to immense students that will arm them with capacity to contribute in the\r\nupliftment of the general welfare and the quality of life of the community and the enhancement of its facilities especially those that are devoted to improving the\r\nhealth, environment, entrepreneurship, safety, recreation and morale of the citizen.','[{\"pilo\":\"understand the basic concepts across the domains of knowledge;\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"demonstrate critical, analytical, and creative thinking;\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"apply the different analytical modes (quantitative and qualitative, artistic and scientific, textual and visual, experimental, observation, etc.) in tackling problems methodically. Personal and Civic Responsibilities\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"develop self-assuredness in knowing and being Filipino;\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"pilo\":\"reflect on moral norms\\/imperatives as they affect individuals and society;\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"pilo\":\"understand and respect for human rights; and\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"pilo\":\"contribute personally and meaningfully to the country\\u2019s development.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"work effectively in a group;\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"manage and handle problem-solving (include real-world problems); and\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"O\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"pilo\":\"demonstrate basic world-related skills and knowledge.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"O\"}]','[{\"cilo\":\"NSTP \\u2013CWTS\\/LTS Curricular Program\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"cilo\":\"Self-Awareness and Self-Management\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Moral Values and Values Development\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Leaders and Leadership\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Conduct Of Off-Campus Activities\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Good Citizenship Values\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"P\"},{\"cilo\":\"Team Building for Youth Organization\",\"ctpss\":\"O\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"L\"},{\"cilo\":\"Decision Making\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Disaster Management\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"L\",\"glc\":\"O\"},{\"cilo\":\"Drug Abuse, Alcoholism and Cigarette Smoking\",\"ctpss\":\"P\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"P\",\"glc\":\"O\"}]','General Education Program aims to:\r\nIntellectual competencies\r\n\r\n1. Understand the basic concepts across the domains of knowledge\r\n2. Apply critical, analytical and creative thinking\r\n3. Communicate proficiently and effectively (writing, speaking and use of new\r\ntechnologies.)\r\n\r\nPersonal and civic responsibilities\r\n\r\n1. Reflect critically on shared concerns and think of innovative, creative solutions\r\nguided by ethical standards.\r\n\r\n2. Reflect on moral norms/imperatives as they affect individuals and society\r\n3. Contribute personally and meaningfully to the country\'s development\r\nPractical skills\r\n1. Work effectively in a group\r\n2. Apply the computing and information technology to assist and facilitate research\r\n3. Demonstrate basic work-related skills and knowledge','At the end of the semester, the students should be able to:\r\nKnowledge:\r\n1. Understand the principles and theories of community service, including its impact on individuals and communities.\r\n2. Recognize the social, cultural, and economic factors influencing community needs and the effectiveness of service interventions.\r\nSkills:\r\n1. Demonstrate the ability to plan, implement, and evaluate community service projects.\r\n2. Develop effective communication and collaboration skills to work with diverse community groups and stakeholders.\r\n3. Apply problem-solving and critical thinking skills to address community issues and assess service outcomes.\r\nAttitudes and Values:\r\n1. Cultivate a commitment to civic responsibility and social justice.\r\n2. Show empathy and respect towards individuals from diverse backgrounds and experiences.\r\n3. Reflect on personal growth and the ethical dimensions of community service.','The nstp students should be able to :\r\n1. explain the key concepts, theories, and principles of community organizing and participatory\r\naction research;\r\n2. demonstrate the ability to design and conduct comprehensive community assessments using\r\nparticipatory methods;\r\n3. collaborate with community members to develop and implement action plans that address\r\nidentified issues and promote community empowerment;\r\n4. demonstrate skills in facilitating community meetings, workshops, and other participatory\r\nactivities that encourage active involvement and leadership from community members; and\r\n5. evaluate the impact of community organizing and participatory action research initiatives and propose strategies for sustainability.','1. Miguel, Cariño (2014), Civic Welfare Training Services (NSTP1), HISGOPHIL Publishing House, Inc.\r\n2. NSTP 1 (LMS), https://bcpedu.elearningcommons.com/\r\n3. Dr. Sonia Gasilla Dela Cruz, NSTP National Development via National service Training Program\r\n4. Dr. Carlie I. Carino and jolly A. Miguel, NSTP 2','1. Smart device with SMS, internet browser, social network, camera, calculator, google: chrome, docs, slides, sheets, meet, microsoft: word,\r\nexcel, ppt, pdf, MODULES, Learning Management System (LMS) and other apps when needed.\r\n2. Internet connection\r\n3. Network access account\r\n4. Physical storage device or virtual drive.','Student must be able to:\r\n1. complete at least 80% of student participation;\r\n2. demonstrate punctuality according to his/her schedule;\r\n3. accomplish alternative assessment (if needed); and\r\n3.1. when student fail to comply or perform poorly in a major examination and/or non-participation because of valid reason e.g. health, force majeure need to provide alternative\r\nassessment Parallel to the Off-Campus Activity and 90 hours of community service.\r\n4. comply the requirements for the off-campus tour\r\n4.1 PRE\r\n4.1.1. Parents Permit\r\n4.1.2. Students and parents’ orientation\r\n4.1.3. Payment official receipt\r\n4.2. DURING\r\n4.2.1. Water jug\r\n4.2.2. extra t-shirt etc.\r\n4.3. AFTER\r\n4.3.1. Submit Portfolio, Documentation, Reflection, narrative report','Cluster Leader:\r\nJustine joy A. Villaruel, LPT\r\nCluster Members:\r\nRenan B. Barata, LPT\r\nShella joy V. Baayos','Faculty Member:\r\nJustine joy A. Villaruel, LPT\r\nRenan B. Barata, LPT\r\nShella joy V. Baayos\r\nJason B. Manlapaz\r\nEmail Address:\r\n010428.jmvg@gmail.com\r\nConsultation Hours:\r\nMonday and Tuesday - 1:00 to 2:30\r\npm\r\nTime and Venue:\r\nAnnex building\r\nOffice of the Program Head','JUSTINE JOY A. VILLARUEL, LPT','MICHAEL L. BERSAMIN, LPT','CHARLIE I. CARIÑO, Ph.D.','2026-02-06 17:41:37','2026-02-06 17:41:37',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
(43,'CAD/CAM)','Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing','Major','Professional Subject Board Courses','CHED',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'{\"Week 0\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nBCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives, Philosophy and School Organizational Structure School Policies Orientation in Online and Modular Learning System,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nRecite, internalize and explain the BCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives and Philosophy\\r\\nDeepen knowledge on the school\'s policies, guidelines, rules and regulations.\\r\\nFamiliarize on the new normal system of education through online, modular learning system and Blended Learning Delivery Modality (BLDM),, Assessment: ONSITE: Identify the Vision and Mission statements of BCP.\\r\\nCritically analyze these statements in 500 words, focusing on the following:\\r\\nThe clarity and coherence of the statements.\\r\\nHow these statements reflect the school\'s commitment to education.\\r\\nThe alignment of these statements with the current educational landscape.\\r\\nVerify that the BCP VMGO are align with the school goals thru checklist (PMED tools) OFFSITE: Navigate LMS and know the function of each feature.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Read and internalize the following printed materials for Students and Parents Orientation: OFF-SITE: Presentation and Lecture Discussion (PowerPoint Presentation) of Students and Parents Orientation:,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nInstructional Materials\\r\\nVideo Presentation of BCP Hymn\\r\\nYouTube Video Title: BESTLINK COLLEGE OF THE PHILIPPINES HYMN (BCP hymn)\\r\\nhttps:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=NuEYO11Wb4E\\r\\nStudent Hand Book\\r\\nLearning Management System,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCheck alignment report\",\"Week 1\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nCourse Orientation; Introduction to Manufacturing Engineering and CAD\\/CAM; Definition, Evolution, and Scope of CAD\\/CAM; Fundamentals of Computer-Aided Design (CAD); Fundamentals of Computer-Aided Manufacturing (CAM); Integration of CAD\\/CAM in Modern Manufacturing and Industry 4.0.,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nDescribe the course objectives, scope, and assessment criteria; Explain the fundamental concepts and significance of CAD\\/CAM in modern manufacturing engineering; Differentiate between CAD and CAM principles and applications; Identify the historical evolution and current trends of CAD\\/CAM technologies; Discuss the benefits and challenges of integrating CAD\\/CAM within the context of Industry 4.0.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Short Quiz on CAD\\/CAM definitions and concepts; Oral Recitation on course expectations and the relevance of CAD\\/CAM in the BSMfgE program. OFFSITE: Reflection Paper on the importance of CAD\\/CAM in the context of Industry 4.0 and sustainable manufacturing; Initial Research Report: Identify and briefly describe one prominent CAD software and one prominent CAM software, outlining their primary functions.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive Lecture and Discussion: Course overview, historical context, definitions, and applications of CAD\\/CAM; Group Brainstorming: Discussing various industries benefiting from CAD\\/CAM technologies; Q&A Session: Clarifying course content and expectations. OFF-SITE: Video Watching: Introductory documentaries or explainer videos on CAD\\/CAM applications in manufacturing (e.g., from software vendors or educational channels); Online Reading: Assigned articles on the evolution of CAD\\/CAM, Industry 4.0, and digital manufacturing; LMS Forum Discussion: Post initial thoughts on career opportunities in manufacturing engineering enhanced by CAD\\/CAM skills.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nCourse Syllabus (digital and print); Lecture Slides (PowerPoint\\/Google Slides); Recommended Textbook: \'CAD\\/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' by Mikell P. Groover and Emory W. Zimmers Jr. (or equivalent contemporary text); Online Articles\\/Journals (e.g., scholarly articles on Industry 4.0 and CAD\\/CAM from IEEE, ASME); Video URLs (e.g., YouTube channels of Autodesk, SolidWorks, Mastercam, Siemens PLM for introductory content); Learning Management System (LMS) platform (e.g., Canvas, Moodle).,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCompleted Short Quiz; Reflection Paper (digital submission); Initial Software Research Report (digital submission); LMS Forum Post.\",\"Week 2\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nIntroduction to CAD Software Environment and Basic 2D Sketching,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Identify and navigate the user interface, toolbars, and features of a standard CAD software (e.g., SolidWorks, Fusion 360, AutoCAD).\\r\\n2. Utilize fundamental sketching tools such as Line, Circle, Arc, Rectangle, and Polygon to create basic 2D geometries.\\r\\n3. Apply geometric constraints (e.g., horizontal, vertical, tangent, concentric, coincident) to define sketch relationships accurately.\\r\\n4. Implement dimensional constraints (e.g., length, radius, angle) to fully define and control 2D sketches.\\r\\n5. Save and manage CAD sketch files effectively, adhering to standard naming conventions.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Practical exercise: Identification of CAD software interface components; Live demonstration and assessment of 2D sketching skills in a laboratory setting; Short quiz on CAD terminology and constraint types. OFFSITE: Homework assignment: Completion of a series of 2D sketching exercises with specified geometric and dimensional constraints; Research and submission of a brief report on the importance of fully defined sketches in CAD.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive lecture and demonstration on CAD software interface and basic sketching tools; Guided laboratory session with hands-on practice on 2D sketching and constraint application; Q&A session for troubleshooting common sketching issues. OFF-SITE: Pre-recorded video tutorials on advanced sketching techniques and constraint applications; Online reading materials on CAD sketching best practices and industry standards; Self-paced practice exercises using provided CAD software licenses or free alternatives; Participation in an online forum discussion on challenges faced during sketching.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nCAD software (e.g., SolidWorks, Fusion 360, AutoCAD) installed in lab computers; Projector\\/Smartboard for live demonstrations; Official CAD software user manuals\\/help documentation; Online tutorial videos (e.g., YouTube, LinkedIn Learning, official vendor channels); Digital slides\\/presentations on CAD interface and 2D sketching principles.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCompleted CAD sketch files (.sldprt, .f3d, .dwg, etc.) for assigned exercises; Lab activity reports documenting steps and observations; Short written report on sketching best practices.\",\"Week 3\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced 2D Sketching and Parametric Constraints\\r\\n- Geometric Constraints (coincident, parallel, perpendicular, tangent, concentric, horizontal, vertical, equal, symmetric)\\r\\n- Dimensional Constraints (linear, angular, radial, diameter)\\r\\n- Fully Defined vs. Under-defined Sketches\\r\\n- Introduction to Parametric Design Principles in 2D\\r\\n- Best Practices for Robust 2D Sketch Creation,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Apply various geometric constraints to accurately define 2D sketches for engineering components.\\r\\n2. Utilize dimensional constraints to precisely control the size and position of sketch entities.\\r\\n3. Differentiate between fully defined and under-defined sketches and explain their implications in parametric design.\\r\\n4. Create robust and parametrically driven 2D sketches as a foundation for 3D modeling.,, Assessment: ONSITE: 1. Hands-on Lab Exercise: Applying Geometric and Dimensional Constraints (graded pass\\/fail or rubric-based).\\r\\n2. Short Quiz: Identification and application of different constraint types. OFFSITE: 1. Homework Assignment: Create fully constrained 2D sketches of two specified mechanical components (e.g., a bracket, a flange) using CAD software.\\r\\n2. Online Forum Discussion: Share and critique peers\' constrained sketches, focusing on efficiency and robustness.,, Activities: ON-SITE: 1. Interactive Lecture and Discussion: In-depth explanation of geometric and dimensional constraints, parametric principles.\\r\\n2. Live Demonstration: Step-by-step demonstration of applying various constraints in a selected CAD software.\\r\\n3. Guided Laboratory Work: Students practice applying constraints on simple and moderately complex 2D shapes under instructor supervision. OFF-SITE: 1. Video Tutorials: Watch curated online videos demonstrating advanced 2D sketching techniques and constraint application in CAD software.\\r\\n2. Online Reading: Review articles or e-book chapters on parametric sketching and design intent.\\r\\n3. Self-Paced Practice: Work on the homework assignment, experimenting with different constraint combinations to achieve design intent.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n1. CAD Software (e.g., SolidWorks, Fusion 360, AutoCAD, Inventor).\\r\\n2. Course Textbook: Chapter on 2D sketching, constraints, and parametric modeling.\\r\\n3. Instructor-prepared Lecture Slides and Handouts on Geometric and Dimensional Constraints.\\r\\n4. Online CAD Tutorials (e.g., YouTube channels, LinkedIn Learning, software-specific forums).\\r\\n5. CAD software\'s built-in help documentation and tutorials.,, Output Materials:\\r\\n1. Completed CAD files (.prt, .sldprt, .f3d, .dwg, etc.) from the hands-on lab exercise.\\r\\n2. Quiz Answer Sheet on constraint types.\\r\\n3. Completed CAD files (.prt, .sldprt, .f3d, .dwg, etc.) for the homework assignment.\\r\\n4. Contributions to the online discussion forum.\",\"Week 4\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nParametric and Feature-Based Modeling for Complex Parts\\r\\n- Advanced Sketching Tools and Techniques (Splines, Patterns, Mirroring)\\r\\n- Complex Solid Modeling Features (Sweeps, Lofts, Shell, Ribs, Draft)\\r\\n- Design Intent and Parametric Relationships\\r\\n- Introduction to Design for Manufacturability (DFM) considerations in CAD,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Apply advanced sketching and feature-based modeling tools (e.g., sweeps, lofts, shells) to construct complex 3D components.\\r\\n2. Implement parametric relationships and design intent to create adaptable and modifiable 3D models.\\r\\n3. Evaluate the impact of different modeling strategies on design flexibility and potential manufacturing processes.,, Assessment: ONSITE: 1. Practical Lab Exercise: Modeling a complex mechanical component with specified features and parametric requirements.\\r\\n2. Short Quiz: On advanced CAD features, design intent, and basic DFM principles. OFFSITE: 1. Design Challenge: Model a given complex industrial part, ensuring parametric control and submitting the CAD file along with a brief design report.\\r\\n2. Online Forum Discussion: Contribute to a discussion on \'Challenges and best practices in modeling complex geometries for manufacturing\'.,, Activities: ON-SITE: 1. Lecture-Demonstration: Instructor-led demonstration of advanced sketching and solid modeling features (e.g., sweeps, lofts, shells, ribs, drafts).\\r\\n2. Hands-on Laboratory Session: Guided practice exercises on applying parametric design and complex feature creation using CAD software.\\r\\n3. Group Discussion: Analyzing case studies of complex parts and discussing DFM considerations during their design. OFF-SITE: 1. Video Tutorials: Watch curated video tutorials on specific advanced CAD functions (e.g., \'Mastering the Loft Command\', \'Parametric Design Strategies\').\\r\\n2. Online Reading: Review articles and white papers on design intent, parametric modeling best practices, and introductory DFM guidelines.\\r\\n3. LMS Quiz: Complete an online quiz assessing understanding of advanced modeling concepts and parametric design principles.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n1. Textbook: \'CAD\\/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' (e.g., by Ibrahim Zeid or similar industry-standard texts).\\r\\n2. Software: Latest versions of industry-standard CAD software (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, CATIA, PTC Creo) with academic licenses.\\r\\n3. Lecture Slides: Visual aids detailing advanced features and parametric design workflows.\\r\\n4. Video Tutorials: Links to reputable online CAD tutorial platforms (e.g., SolidWorks official tutorials, YouTube channels).\\r\\n5. Online Articles\\/Journals: Resources on DFM in CAD and advanced modeling techniques.,, Output Materials:\\r\\n1. CAD Part Files (.SLDPRT, .IPT, .CATPart) of complex components.\\r\\n2. Short Design Report detailing parametric strategy and DFM considerations.\\r\\n3. Completed Lab Worksheets.\\r\\n4. Quiz results (on-site and off-site).\\r\\n5. Online Forum contributions.\",\"Week 5\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced Part Modeling Techniques and Introduction to Assembly Design,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nApply advanced part modeling features such as sweeps, lofts, shells, ribs, and patterns to create complex 3D geometries.,Analyze the appropriate use cases for different advanced modeling techniques in manufacturing design scenarios.,Demonstrate the ability to create basic product assemblies using standard mating and constraint techniques (e.g., coincident, concentric, parallel, perpendicular).,, Assessment: ONSITE: Practical CAD Lab Exercise: Design and model a complex component requiring advanced features (e.g., a bottle, a turbine blade segment, a complex bracket).,Short Quiz: Identification and application of advanced modeling features and basic assembly concepts. OFFSITE: Individual Design Project: Create a 3D model of a specified industrial part using at least three advanced modeling techniques and assemble it with a simple mating component.,Research and Report: Investigate the industry applications of advanced surfacing or solid modeling techniques in a chosen manufacturing sector (e.g., automotive, aerospace, consumer electronics).,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture-Demonstration: In-depth explanation and live software demonstration of advanced part modeling features (sweep, loft, shell, patterns, ribs) with practical examples.,Hands-on Laboratory Work: Guided exercises in CAD software to practice creating complex parts and simple assemblies.,Group Problem-Solving: Students work in small groups to collaboratively design a part requiring specific advanced features, discussing optimal modeling strategies. OFF-SITE: Video Watching: Access curated online video tutorials on advanced CAD features and basic assembly workflows (e.g., specific SolidWorks\\/Fusion 360\\/CATIA tutorials).,Online Reading: Review digital textbook chapters or articles on advanced modeling techniques, design intent, and assembly strategies.,LMS Practice Quizzes: Self-assessment quizzes on advanced feature definitions and their applications.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nTextbook: \'CAD\\/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' by P.N. Rao (or similar contemporary texts).,Software: Industry-standard CAD software (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Fusion 360, PTC Creo, CATIA) installed in lab or accessible via student licenses.,Slides: Detailed presentation slides illustrating advanced modeling commands and assembly principles.,Video URL: Links to official software tutorials and reputable YouTube channels demonstrating advanced CAD features (e.g., \'SolidWorks Advanced Part Modeling Tutorial\', \'Fusion 360 Assembly Basics\').,Online Resources: Manufacturer\'s documentation for CAD software, CAD community forums, engineering design blogs.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCAD Part Files (.SLDPRT, .F3D, .CATPart, .PRT) demonstrating complex geometries.,CAD Assembly Files (.SLDASM, .F3Z, .CATProduct, .ASM) for basic product assemblies.,Short Research Report\\/Documentation (PDF) on industry applications of advanced modeling, including screenshots of models.\",\"Week 6\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nPrelim Exam\",\"Week 7\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nGeometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing (GD&T) Principles and Applications in CAD\\r\\n- Review of traditional dimensioning and tolerancing limitations.\\r\\n- Introduction to GD&T concepts: feature control frames, datums, form, orientation, location, runout, and profile tolerances.\\r\\n- GD&T symbols and their interpretation (e.g., ASME Y14.5 standard).\\r\\n- Importance of GD&T in manufacturing for quality control, interchangeability, and assembly.\\r\\n- Practical application of GD&T in CAD software for part design and assembly.,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Explain the fundamental principles and symbols of Geometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing (GD&T).\\r\\n2. Interpret engineering drawings that incorporate GD&T specifications effectively.\\r\\n3. Apply appropriate GD&T features to CAD models to ensure design intent, manufacturing accuracy, and functionality.\\r\\n4. Evaluate the impact of GD&T on product quality, assembly efficiency, and cost-effectiveness in modern manufacturing processes.,, Assessment: ONSITE: 1. Quiz on GD&T symbols, definitions, and interpretation.\\r\\n2. Practical CAD exercise: Applying GD&T to a given mechanical component model within CAD software. OFFSITE: 1. Analysis of an industrial engineering drawing containing complex GD&T specifications.\\r\\n2. Research and present a short report on a case study where GD&T significantly improved a manufacturing process or product quality.,, Activities: ON-SITE: 1. Interactive lecture and discussion on GD&T standards (e.g., ASME Y14.5) and best practices.\\r\\n2. Hands-on CAD laboratory session focusing on applying GD&T features in design software.\\r\\n3. Group problem-solving exercises interpreting and correcting GD&T errors in sample drawings. OFF-SITE: 1. Watch curated instructional videos on advanced GD&T concepts and applications (e.g., specific tolerance types).\\r\\n2. Online reading assignments on the latest GD&T standards and industry trends.\\r\\n3. Participate in an online discussion forum addressing challenges and solutions in GD&T implementation.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n1. Textbook: \'Geometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing for Design, Manufacturing, and Inspection\' (e.g., by James D. Meadows).\\r\\n2. CAD Software (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, Fusion 360) with GD&T functionalities.\\r\\n3. Lecture slides and notes on GD&T principles, symbols, and rules.\\r\\n4. Online resources: ASME Y14.5 standard excerpts, industry whitepapers on GD&T, YouTube tutorials on CAD GD&T application.\\r\\n5. Sample industrial engineering drawings with GD&T specifications.,, Output Materials:\\r\\n1. Completed CAD models with correctly applied GD&T features, demonstrating design intent.\\r\\n2. Quiz results demonstrating understanding of GD&T concepts.\\r\\n3. Written analysis report of an industrial drawing with GD&T specifications.\\r\\n4. Short research report on a GD&T case study in manufacturing.\",\"Week 8\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced CAD Modeling Techniques and Assemblies,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nApply advanced surfacing techniques (e.g., lofts, sweeps, boundary surfaces) to create complex geometric shapes for product design.,Construct and manage multi-part assemblies using appropriate mating conditions and assembly constraints.,Analyze the kinematic behavior of simple assemblies to understand motion and interference.,Evaluate the impact of different modeling strategies on design intent and downstream manufacturing processes.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Midterm Exam (Theory and Practical Application), Assembly Design Challenge OFFSITE: Research paper on emerging CAD modeling trends (e.g., generative design, parametric optimization), Individual assembly project report,, Activities: ON-SITE: Lecture on advanced surfacing and assembly techniques, Hands-on laboratory session for complex modeling and assembly creation, Case study analysis of product assemblies, Peer review of assembly designs OFF-SITE: Online tutorials for advanced CAD features, Interactive simulation exercises for assembly kinematics, Reading assignments on assembly best practices and design for manufacturability (DFM),, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nCAD Software (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, CATIA) with advanced modules,Lecture slides on advanced surfacing and assembly,Video tutorials for specific CAD commands and techniques,Textbook chapters on advanced CAD modeling,Online resources for assembly simulation and analysis,, Output Materials:\\r\\nComplex 3D CAD models of individual parts, Fully constrained multi-part assemblies, Assembly simulation results, Research paper on advanced CAD trends, Midterm Exam paper\",\"Week 9\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nIntroduction to Additive Manufacturing (AM) and its Integration with CAD\\/CAM Workflows:\\r\\n- Principles of AM (3D Printing) Technologies (e.g., FDM, SLA, SLM, SLS)\\r\\n- CAD for AM: Design considerations, advanced modeling techniques (e.g., lattice structures, generative design, topology optimization)\\r\\n- CAM for AM: Slicing software, support generation, build plate optimization, process parameters\\r\\n- Post-processing and quality control in AM\\r\\n- Applications of AM in Manufacturing Engineering (prototyping, tooling, functional parts, mass customization),, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Explain the fundamental principles and various technologies of Additive Manufacturing (AM).\\r\\n2. Analyze design considerations and advanced modeling techniques (e.g., lattice structures, topology optimization) specifically for AM using CAD software.\\r\\n3. Apply CAM principles for AM, including slicing, support generation, and build orientation optimization.\\r\\n4. Evaluate the advantages and limitations of integrating AM into traditional manufacturing workflows.\\r\\n5. Propose suitable AM processes for specific manufacturing engineering applications based on design requirements and material properties.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Short Quiz on AM principles and CAD for AM concepts.\\r\\nGroup Discussion and Presentation on case studies of AM applications in different industries. OFFSITE: Design an AM-optimized component (e.g., lightweight bracket with lattice structure or topology-optimized part) using CAD software, submitting the CAD file and a brief design justification report.\\r\\nResearch paper on a specific AM technology\'s impact on a chosen manufacturing industry, including its CAD\\/CAM integration challenges and solutions.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive Lecture on AM principles, technologies, and workflow integration.\\r\\nHands-on CAD laboratory session focusing on designing for AM (e.g., using generative design tools, lattice features, or preparing models for slicing).\\r\\nCase Study Analysis and Group Presentation on real-world AM applications and challenges. OFF-SITE: Watch curated video tutorials on specific AM technologies (e.g., FDM, SLA, SLM) and dedicated slicing software.\\r\\nOnline Reading materials on topology optimization, lattice structure generation, and AM standards.\\r\\nParticipate in an LMS discussion forum on the ethical implications and future trends of AM in manufacturing.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nTextbook chapters on Additive Manufacturing, Rapid Prototyping, and Digital Manufacturing.\\r\\nCAD Software with Generative Design\\/Topology Optimization modules (e.g., Autodesk Fusion 360, SolidWorks, nTopology, Netfabb).\\r\\nSlicing Software (e.g., Ultimaker Cura, Simplify3D, PrusaSlicer, specific machine software).\\r\\nAcademic papers and industry reports on AM applications and design guidelines.\\r\\nVideo URLs: \'Introduction to 3D Printing Technologies\', \'Designing for Additive Manufacturing\', \'Topology Optimization Explained\', \'Additive Manufacturing Workflow\'.\\r\\nLecture slides and supplementary notes.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nQuiz Answer Sheet.\\r\\nGroup Discussion Summary\\/Presentation Slides.\\r\\nCAD Model file (.STL, .STEP, or native format) of an AM-optimized component.\\r\\nBrief Design Justification Report (PDF).\\r\\nResearch Paper on AM technology\'s impact on manufacturing.\",\"Week 10\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced CAM Strategies and Multi-axis Machining,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Evaluate various advanced CAM strategies (e.g., high-speed machining, adaptive machining, trochoidal milling) for complex part manufacturing. 2. Apply multi-axis machining techniques (e.g., 4-axis, 5-axis simultaneous) to generate optimized toolpaths for intricate geometries. 3. Analyze the impact of advanced CAM parameters on machining efficiency, surface finish, and tool life. 4. Propose suitable multi-axis machining solutions for specific manufacturing challenges based on part complexity and material properties.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Practical Lab Exercise: Multi-axis Toolpath Generation; Short Quiz on Advanced CAM Concepts and Terminology; Group Discussion on Multi-axis Machining Applications. OFFSITE: Case Study Analysis: Industrial Application of Advanced CAM; Simulation Report on a Multi-axis Machining Project; Research on Post-processing for 5-axis CNC Machines.,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive Lecture on Advanced CAM methodologies and Multi-axis kinematics; Hands-on CAD\\/CAM Software Lab Session (e.g., Mastercam, NX CAM, Fusion 360) for multi-axis toolpath programming; Demonstrations of advanced toolpath generation and simulation; Collaborative problem-solving for optimizing machining strategies. OFF-SITE: Online video tutorials on specific advanced CAM features and multi-axis programming techniques; Online reading materials (academic papers, industry articles) on high-performance machining and advanced toolpath optimization; Participation in an online discussion forum on challenges and best practices in multi-axis machining; Self-paced practice exercises using CAD\\/CAM software.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nTextbook chapters on Advanced CAM and Multi-axis Machining; CAD\\/CAM software manuals and help documentation (e.g., Mastercam, NX CAM, Fusion 360 user guides); Online resources from software vendors (e.g., Autodesk, Siemens PLM, CNC Software Inc.); Academic journals on manufacturing engineering and advanced machining; Video tutorials on advanced CAM strategies (e.g., YouTube channels of software providers, NCMT); Sample multi-axis CAD models for practice.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nGenerated multi-axis toolpaths and associated NC files; Detailed simulation reports of machining operations; Completed quiz on advanced CAM; Written case study analysis report; Research summary on post-processing for 5-axis machines.\",\"Week 11\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced CAM Programming and Simulation: Multi-Axis Machining\\r\\n- Introduction to Multi-Axis Machining (3-axis vs. 4-axis vs. 5-axis)\\r\\n- Kinematics and Tool Orientations in Multi-Axis Machining\\r\\n- Advanced Toolpath Strategies for Multi-Axis Operations (e.g., Swarf, Flowline, Contour)\\r\\n- Collision Detection and Avoidance in Multi-Axis Simulation\\r\\n- Post-Processing for Multi-Axis CNC Machines\\r\\n- Optimization Techniques for Multi-Axis Toolpaths,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Analyze the principles and applications of 4-axis and 5-axis machining in complex manufacturing scenarios.\\r\\n2. Develop advanced CAM programs for multi-axis parts using specialized software features.\\r\\n3. Perform comprehensive simulations of multi-axis machining processes to identify and resolve potential issues like collisions and gouges.\\r\\n4. Evaluate various multi-axis toolpath strategies for efficiency, surface quality, and material removal rates.\\r\\n5. Generate and interpret post-processed G-code for multi-axis CNC machines.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Practical Lab Exam: Multi-Axis CAM Programming and Simulation (Students program and simulate a complex 4\\/5-axis part). OFFSITE: Multi-Axis Machining Case Study Report (Students analyze a real-world application of multi-axis machining and propose an optimized CAM strategy).,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive Lecture: Principles and Applications of Multi-Axis Machining; Hands-on Laboratory Session: Multi-Axis CAM Software Proficiency (e.g., generating toolpaths for a turbine blade or impeller); Live Demonstration: Advanced Simulation Features and Collision Detection. OFF-SITE: Curated Video Tutorials on Specific Multi-Axis CAM Software Modules; Online Reading: Research papers and industry articles on the latest trends in 5-axis machining; LMS-based Discussion Forum: Challenges and solutions in multi-axis post-processing.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nTextbook: \'Computer-Aided Manufacturing\' by Tien-Chien Chang, Richard A. Wysk, Hsu-Pin Wang (relevant chapters on advanced CAM); CAD\\/CAM Software: Siemens NX CAM, Mastercam, CATIA V5\\/V6 (with multi-axis modules installed); Online Resources: Official software documentation and tutorials (e.g., Siemens NX Learn, Mastercam University), YouTube channels (e.g., Haas Automation, Mazak, DMG Mori); Academic Papers: IEEE, ASME, CIRP publications on advanced manufacturing and multi-axis machining; Instructor-prepared lecture slides, lab manuals, and sample CAD models for multi-axis parts.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCompleted Multi-Axis CAM Program Files (.NC, .APT, or native CAM file); Detailed Multi-Axis Machining Simulation Report (including collision analysis, cycle time, and material removal rate); Written Case Study Report on Multi-Axis Machining Application.\",\"Week 12\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMidterm Exam\",\"Week 13\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMulti-axis Machining and Advanced CAM Strategies,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Analyze the applications and benefits of multi-axis machining in complex part manufacturing. 2. Generate multi-axis toolpaths using CAD\\/CAM software for specific part geometries. 3. Evaluate and optimize advanced CAM strategies (e.g., High-Speed Machining, Adaptive Clearing) to improve machining efficiency and surface quality. 4. Identify and mitigate potential collisions in multi-axis machining simulations.,, Assessment: ONSITE: 1. Practical Lab Exam: Multi-axis toolpath generation and simulation. 2. Group Problem-Solving Activity: Optimizing a multi-axis machining scenario. OFFSITE: 1. Case Study Analysis: Research and report on an industry application of 5-axis machining. 2. CAM Project Part 3: Develop and simulate advanced CAM strategies for a complex part (e.g., impeller, turbine blade).,, Activities: ON-SITE: 1. Interactive Lecture: Principles of multi-axis kinematics and advanced toolpath types. 2. CAD\\/CAM Software Hands-on Lab: Guided exercises on 4-axis and 5-axis toolpath creation and simulation. 3. Demonstration: Live software demonstration of advanced CAM features and collision detection. 4. Group Discussion: Pros and cons of different advanced CAM strategies in specific manufacturing contexts. OFF-SITE: 1. Video Tutorials: Watch manufacturer-specific tutorials on advanced CAM features (e.g., Autodesk Fusion 360, Mastercam, SolidCAM). 2. Online Reading: Articles and white papers on High-Speed Machining, Adaptive Clearing, and multi-axis applications. 3. LMS Forum Discussion: Share insights on industry trends and challenges in multi-axis machining. 4. Simulation Practice: Independent practice on generating and verifying multi-axis toolpaths and advanced strategies in CAD\\/CAM software.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n1. Textbook Chapters: Advanced CAM, Multi-axis Machining. 2. CAD\\/CAM Software (e.g., Fusion 360, Mastercam, SolidCAM, CATIA, Siemens NX). 3. Instructor-prepared slides and lab manuals for multi-axis machining. 4. Video Tutorials: e.g., \'5-Axis Machining Fundamentals\' (YouTube), \'Adaptive Clearing Explained\' (Software vendor channels). 5. Technical Papers\\/Articles on High-Speed Machining and multi-axis applications. 6. Sample 3D models for multi-axis machining exercises.,, Output Materials:\\r\\n1. Completed CAD\\/CAM software files with multi-axis toolpaths and advanced strategies (.f3d, .mcx, .sldprt, etc.). 2. Simulation reports\\/screenshots of toolpath verification and collision analysis. 3. Case study report on multi-axis applications. 4. CAM Project Part 3 documentation (toolpath description, cutting parameters, simulation results, optimization rationale).\",\"Week 14\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced CAM Strategies and Integration with Manufacturing Systems (Robotics & Automation),, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nAnalyze the principles and applications of advanced CAM strategies for complex geometries and multi-axis machining; Evaluate the role of CAD\\/CAM in robotic programming and automated manufacturing cells; Design a basic integrated CAD\\/CAM-robotics workflow for a specific manufacturing task; Propose solutions for optimizing manufacturing processes through CAD\\/CAM and automation integration.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group Presentation: Case Study on Integrated CAD\\/CAM-Robotics in Manufacturing OFFSITE: Design and Simulation Project: Robotic Path Planning and Collision Avoidance using CAD\\/CAM Data,, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive Lecture: Advanced CAM techniques (e.g., 5-axis machining, feature-based machining, high-speed machining); Laboratory Session: Hands-on exploration of CAD\\/CAM software for robot programming and simulation; Group Discussion: Challenges and opportunities in CAD\\/CAM integration with Industry 4.0 technologies. OFF-SITE: Video Watching: Case studies on advanced robotic manufacturing cells and automated production lines (e.g., automotive, aerospace); Online Reading: Research papers or articles on advanced CAM algorithms, human-robot collaboration, and digital twins in manufacturing; LMS Quiz: Conceptual understanding of advanced CAM and automation integration.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nTextbook: Groover, M. P. (2020). *Fundamentals of Modern Manufacturing: Materials, Processes, and Systems*. (Relevant chapters on automation, robotics, and advanced CAM); Software: Siemens NX CAM, CATIA, SolidWorks CAM, Mastercam (with advanced modules for multi-axis machining and robot simulation); Video URL: Industry 4.0 manufacturing facility tours, robotic welding\\/assembly demonstrations (e.g., KUKA, FANUC educational videos); Online Articles: Peer-reviewed journals on advanced manufacturing automation (e.g., IEEE Xplore, ScienceDirect); Lecture Slides: \'Advanced CAM and Robotics Integration.\',, Output Materials:\\r\\nGroup Presentation Slides; Simulation Report (Robotic Path Planning); CAD\\/CAM Software Files (e.g., 5-axis toolpaths, robot cell layout, simulation results); LMS Quiz Results.\",\"Week 15\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced CAD\\/CAM Integration for Industry 4.0 and Smart Manufacturing \\/ Final Project Presentation and Defense,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nEvaluate the role of advanced CAD\\/CAM systems in Industry 4.0 and smart manufacturing environments; Demonstrate the ability to integrate complex CAD designs with CAM strategies for automated production; Present and defend a comprehensive CAD\\/CAM project, showcasing design, simulation, and manufacturing planning; Propose innovative solutions to manufacturing challenges leveraging integrated CAD\\/CAM technologies.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Final Project Presentation and Oral Defense; Peer Evaluation of Project Presentations. OFFSITE: Submission of Final Project Report; Submission of CAD\\/CAM Project Portfolio (including models, simulations, and toolpaths).,, Activities: ON-SITE: Student-led Project Presentations; Q&A sessions and constructive feedback; Expert panel discussion (if available) on Industry 4.0 applications of CAD\\/CAM; Peer review workshops for project reports. OFF-SITE: Review and refinement of project documentation; Collaborative online refinement of project reports and presentations; Research and analysis of current trends in smart manufacturing and Industry 4.0; Online forum discussion on future directions of CAD\\/CAM.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nProject Guidelines and Rubrics; Advanced CAD\\/CAM Software (e.g., SolidWorks, CATIA, Siemens NX, Fusion 360, Mastercam); Academic papers and industry whitepapers on Industry 4.0, IoT in manufacturing, and smart factories; Case studies of integrated CAD\\/CAM systems in advanced manufacturing; Online tutorials for advanced software features.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nFinal CAD\\/CAM Project Report; Project Presentation Slides\\/Video; Complete CAD Models (native files); CAM Toolpaths and Simulation Files; Manufacturing Process Plan; Peer Evaluation Forms.\",\"Week 16\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nFinal Project Presentations: Integrated CAD\\/CAM System Design and Manufacturing Implementation,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Synthesize and apply advanced CAD\\/CAM principles to design, simulate, and plan the manufacturing of a complex product. \\r\\n2. Present a comprehensive final project, effectively communicating design rationale, manufacturing strategies, and achieved outcomes. \\r\\n3. Defend technical choices and justify the economic and operational benefits of the proposed CAD\\/CAM solution.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Final Project Oral Presentation and Demonstration; Q&A Session with Instructors and Peers. OFFSITE: Submission of Comprehensive Final Project Report (including all supporting files).,, Activities: ON-SITE: Student Project Presentations; Instructor and Peer Feedback Session; Moderated Discussion on project challenges and solutions. OFF-SITE: Independent Final Project Refinement; Preparation of Presentation Materials; Review of Peer Feedback and Self-Reflection.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nComprehensive CAD\\/CAM software suites (e.g., SolidWorks, CATIA, Fusion 360, Mastercam, Siemens NX); Project guidelines and rubrics; Online academic resources for advanced manufacturing case studies; Presentation software and audiovisual equipment.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nFinal Project Report (digital submission); Presentation Slides\\/Demonstration Files; CAD Model Files (e.g., .SLDPRT, .STEP); CAM Toolpath Files (e.g., .NC, .G-code); Simulation Results (e.g., FEA reports, process simulations); Bill of of Materials (BOM).\",\"Week 17\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nAdvanced Manufacturing Strategies and Industry 4.0 Integration with CAD\\/CAM,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\n1. Analyze the impact of Industry 4.0 technologies (e.g., IoT, AI, Big Data, Cloud Computing) on CAD\\/CAM workflows and manufacturing processes. 2. Evaluate advanced manufacturing strategies such as smart manufacturing, digital twins, and additive manufacturing for their integration potential with CAD\\/CAM systems. 3. Propose innovative solutions for real-world manufacturing challenges by leveraging integrated CAD\\/CAM and Industry 4.0 concepts.,, Assessment: ONSITE: Group Presentation: \'Industry 4.0 Case Study and CAD\\/CAM Integration Proposal\' OFFSITE: Research Paper: \'Future Trends in CAD\\/CAM, Smart Manufacturing, and Cybersecurity\',, Activities: ON-SITE: Interactive Lecture on Industry 4.0 pillars and their relevance to CAD\\/CAM; Case Study Analysis and Group Discussion on successful smart manufacturing implementations; Expert Guest Speaker (virtual or in-person) on Smart Factories and Digital Transformation. OFF-SITE: Watch curated documentaries\\/webinars on Smart Manufacturing and Digital Twins; Online research on specific digital twin applications in different industries; Participate in an LMS forum discussion on the ethical implications and cybersecurity challenges of AI in manufacturing.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nTextbook Chapter: \'Industry 4.0 and Advanced Manufacturing\'; Academic Papers\\/Journals on Digital Twins, IoT in Manufacturing, AI in Design Automation; Video URLs: Siemens Digital Enterprise Suite overview, Dassault Syst\\u00e8mes 3DEXPERIENCE platform; Simulation Software (e.g., Ansys, Abaqus for advanced analysis concepts); Online articles from Deloitte, McKinsey, World Economic Forum on Industry 4.0 and future manufacturing.,, Output Materials:\\r\\nGroup Presentation Slides and Report; Comprehensive Research Paper; Discussion Forum Posts.\",\"Week 18\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nFinal Exam\"}',NULL,3,NULL,NULL,'The Bachelor of Science in Manufacturing Engineering (BSMfgE) is a multidisciplinary program focusing on designing, optimizing, and managing production processes, materials, and systems. It prepares students to improve efficiency, quality, and automation from product design to final assembly, combining engineering principles with management techniques','[{\"pilo\":\"Materials and Manufacturing Processes: Understanding how raw materials are transformed into finished products.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"P\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"P\"}]','[{\"cilo\":\"Product, Tooling, and Assembly Engineering: Focus on the design and maintenance of the tools used in production.\",\"ctpss\":\"L\",\"ecc\":\"L\",\"epp\":\"O\",\"glc\":\"P\"}]','The Bachelor of Science in Manufacturing Engineering (BSMfgE) program is designed to produce graduates capable of designing, optimizing, and managing production systems, materials, and processes','A Bachelor of Science in Manufacturing Engineering (BSMfgE) is designed to produce graduates capable of designing, optimizing, and managing complex production systems and processes. The Course Intended Learning Outcomes (CILOs)—often termed Program Outcomes (POs) or Student Outcomes (SOs)—typically align with industry standards like ABET, focusing on technical competence, design, and professional responsibility.','based teaching and learning (OBTL) is an approach where\r\nteaching and learning activities are developed to support the learning\r\noutcomes. It is a student-centered approach for the delivery of\r\neducational programs where the curriculum topics in a program and the\r\ncourses contained in it are expressed as the intended outcomes for\r\nstudents to learn. It is an approach in which teachers facilitate and\r\nstudents find themselves actively engaged in their learning.\r\nIts primary focus is the clear statement of what students should be able\r\nto do after taking a course, known as the Intended Learning Outcomes\r\n(ILOs). The ILOs describe what the learners will be able to do when they\r\nhave completed their course or program. These are statements, written\r\nfrom the students\' perspective, indicating the level of understanding and\r\nperformance they are expected to achieve as a result of engaging in\r\nteaching and learning experience. Once the ILOs have been determined,\r\nthe next step in OBTL is to design the Teaching / Learning Activities\r\n(TLAs) which require students to actively participate in the construction of\r\ntheir new knowledge and abilities. A TLA is any activity which stimulates,\r\nencourages or facilitates learning of one or more intended learning\r\noutcome. The final OBTL component is the Assessment Tasks (ATs),\r\nwhich measure how well students can use their new abilities to solve realworld problems, design, demonstrate creativity, and communicate\r\neffectively, among others. An AT can be any method of assessing how\r\nwell a set of ILO has been achieved.','Curtis, M. Handbook of Dimensional Measurement. Industrial Press, Inc.; 5 edition, 2013.\r\nDotson, C. Fundamentals of Dimensional Metrology. Delmar Cengage Learning: 6 edition,\r\n2015.\r\nKochsiek, Manfred and Michael Glaser. Handbook of Metrology, 2010.\r\nExtended Readings /','BCP Learning Management System (LMS):\r\nhttps://bcpeducollege.elearningcommons.com/login/index.php\r\nOnline Resources: YouTube, etc.','Student must be able to:\r\n1. complete at least 80% of student participation;\r\n2. demonstrate punctuality according to his/her schedule; and,\r\n3. accomplish alternative assessment (if needed)\r\n3.1. when student fail to comply or perform poorly in a major examination\r\nand/or non-participation because of valid reason e.g. health, force majeure\r\nneeds to\r\nprovide alternative assessment such as project, presentation, oral\r\nexamination, and research output','Cluster Leader:\r\nMs. Eliza O. Gomba, LPT\r\nMember:\r\nMs. Divine Grace S. Rapsing, LPT','Cluster Leader:\r\nMs. Eliza O. Gomba, LPT\r\nEmail Address: missyelayg.bcps@gmail.com\r\nConsultation Hours:\r\nMonday-Thursday, 3-5PM\r\nTime and Venue: General Education Office\r\nFaculty Member:\r\nMs. Divine Grace Rapsing\r\nEmail Address: rapsingdivine.12@gmail.com\r\nConsultation Hours:\r\nMonday, 1PM-7PM\r\nTime and Venue: CRAD Office','ELIZA O. GOMBA, LPT','MICHAEL L. BERSAMIN, LPT','CHARLIE I. CARIÑO, Ph.D.','2026-03-31 14:25:33','2026-03-31 14:25:33',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
(44,'CHMRTY-ENG','Chemistry for Engineers','Major','Professional Subject Board Courses','CHED',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'{\"Week 0\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nBCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives, Philosophy and School Organizational Structure School Policies Orientation in Online and Modular Learning System,, Student Intended Learning Outcomes:\\r\\nRecite, internalize and explain the BCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives and Philosophy\\r\\nDeepen knowledge on the school\'s policies, guidelines, rules and regulations.\\r\\nFamiliarize on the new normal system of education through online, modular learning system and Blended Learning Delivery Modality (BLDM),, Assessment: ONSITE: Identify the Vision and Mission statements of BCP.\\r\\nCritically analyze these statements in 500 words, focusing on the following:\\r\\nThe clarity and coherence of the statements.\\r\\nHow these statements reflect the school\'s commitment to education.\\r\\nThe alignment of these statements with the current educational landscape.\\r\\nVerify that the BCP VMGO are align with the school goals thru checklist (PMED tools) OFFSITE: Navigate LMS and know the function of each feature.,, Activities: ON-SITE: materials for Students and Parents Orientation: OFF-SITE: and Modular Learning System\\r\\nStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: Recite, internalize and\\r\\nexplain the BCP Vision, Mission, Goals, Objectives and Philosophy\\r\\nDeepen knowledge on the school\'s policies, guidelines, rules and\\r\\nregulations. Familiarize on the new normal system of education\\r\\nthrough online, modular learning system and Blended Learning\\r\\nDelivery Modality (BLDM)\\r\\nAssessment Tasks (ATs):\\r\\nONSITE: Identify the Vision and Mission statements of BCP. Critically\\r\\nanalyze these statements in 500 words, focusing on the following:\\r\\nThe clarity and coherence of the statements. How these statements\\r\\nre\\ufb02ect the school\'s commitment to education. The alignment of\\r\\nthese statements with the current educational landscape. Verify that\\r\\nthe BCP VMGO are align with the school goals thru checklist (PMED\\r\\ntools)\\r\\nOFFSITE: Navigate LMS and know the function of each feature.\\r\\nSuggested Teaching\\/Learning Activities (TLAs):\\r\\nFace to Face (On-Site): Read and internalize the following printed\\r\\nmaterials for Students and Parents Orientation:\\r\\nOnline (O\\ufb00-Site): Presentation and Lecture Discussion (PowerPoint\\r\\nPresentation) of Students and Parents Orientation:,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nMaterials Video Presentation of BCP Hymn YouTube Video Title:\\r\\nBESTLINK COLLEGE OF THE PHILIPPINES HYMN (BCP hymn)\\r\\nhttps:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=NuEYO11Wb4E Student Hand\\r\\nBook Learning Management System,, Output Materials:\\r\\nCheck alignment report\",\"Week 1\":\"Activities: ON-SITE:  OFF-SITE: scholarly articles on Industry 4.0 and CAD\\/CAM from IEEE, ASME);\\r\\nVideo URLs (e.g., YouTube channels of Autodesk, SolidWorks,\\r\\nMastercam, Siemens PLM for introductory content); Learning\\r\\nManagement System (LMS) platform (e.g., Canvas, Moodle).,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nSyllabus (digital and print); Lecture Slides (PowerPoint\\/Google\\r\\nSlides); Recommended Textbook: \'CAD\\/CAM: Computer-Aided Design\\r\\nand Manufacturing\' by Mikell P. Groover and Emory W. Zimmers Jr.\\r\\n(or equivalent contemporary text); Online Articles\\/Journals (e.g.,\\r\\nscholarly articles on Industry 4.0 and CAD\\/CAM from IEEE, ASME);\\r\\nVideo URLs (e.g., YouTube channels of Autodesk, SolidWorks,\\r\\nMastercam, Siemens PLM for introductory content); Learning\\r\\nManagement System (LMS) platform (e.g., Canvas, Moodle).\",\"Week 2\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: CAD software interface and basic sketching tools; Guided laboratory\\r\\nsession with hands-on practice on 2D sketching and constraint\\r\\napplication; Q&A session for troubleshooting common sketching\\r\\nissues. OFF-SITE: sketching techniques and constraint applications; Online reading\\r\\nmaterials on CAD sketching best practices and industry standards;\\r\\nSelf-paced practice exercises using provided CAD software licenses\\r\\nor free alternatives; Participation in an online forum discussion on\\r\\nchallenges faced during sketching.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nsoftware (e.g., SolidWorks, Fusion 360, AutoCAD) installed in lab\\r\\ncomputers; Projector\\/Smartboard for live demonstrations; O\\ufb03cial\\r\\nCAD software user manuals\\/help documentation; Online tutorial\\r\\nvideos (e.g., YouTube, LinkedIn Learning, o\\ufb03cial vendor channels);\\r\\nDigital slides\\/presentations on CAD interface and 2D sketching\\r\\nprinciples.\",\"Week 3\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: depth explanation of geometric and dimensional constraints,\\r\\nparametric principles. 2. Live Demonstration: Step-by-step\\r\\ndemonstration of applying various constraints in a selected CAD\\r\\nsoftware. 3. Guided Laboratory Work: Students practice applying\\r\\nconstraints on simple and moderately complex 2D shapes under\\r\\ninstructor supervision. OFF-SITE: critique peers\' constrained sketches, focusing on e\\ufb03ciency and\\r\\nrobustness.\\r\\nSuggested Teaching\\/Learning Activities (TLAs):\\r\\nFace to Face (On-Site): 1. Interactive Lecture and Discussion: In-\\r\\ndepth explanation of geometric and dimensional constraints,\\r\\nparametric principles. 2. Live Demonstration: Step-by-step\\r\\ndemonstration of applying various constraints in a selected CAD\\r\\nsoftware. 3. Guided Laboratory Work: Students practice applying\\r\\nconstraints on simple and moderately complex 2D shapes under\\r\\ninstructor supervision.\\r\\nOnline (O\\ufb00-Site): 1. Video Tutorials: Watch curated online videos\\r\\ndemonstrating advanced 2D sketching techniques and constraint\\r\\napplication in CAD software. 2. Online Reading: Review articles or e-\\r\\nbook chapters on parametric sketching and design intent. 3. Self-\\r\\nPaced Practice: Work on the homework assignment, experimenting\\r\\nwith di\\ufb00erent constraint combinations to achieve design intent.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nSoftware (e.g., SolidWorks, Fusion 360, AutoCAD, Inventor). 2.\\r\\nCourse Textbook: Chapter on 2D sketching, constraints, and\\r\\nparametric modeling. 3. Instructor-prepared Lecture Slides and\\r\\nHandouts on Geometric and Dimensional Constraints. 4. Online CAD\\r\\nTutorials (e.g., YouTube channels, LinkedIn Learning, software-\\r\\nspeci\\ufb01c forums). 5. CAD software\'s built-in help documentation and\\r\\ntutorials.\",\"Week 4\":\"Activities: ON-SITE:  OFF-SITE: YouTube channels). 5. Online Articles\\/Journals: Resources on DFM in\\r\\nCAD and advanced modeling techniques.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n\'CAD\\/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' (e.g., by\\r\\nIbrahim Zeid or similar industry-standard texts). 2. Software: Latest\\r\\nversions of industry-standard CAD software (e.g., SolidWorks,\\r\\nAutodesk Inventor, CATIA, PTC Creo) with academic licenses. 3.\\r\\nLecture Slides: Visual aids detailing advanced features and\\r\\nparametric design work\\ufb02ows. 4. Video Tutorials: Links to reputable\\r\\nonline CAD tutorial platforms (e.g., SolidWorks o\\ufb03cial tutorials,\\r\\nYouTube channels). 5. Online Articles\\/Journals: Resources on DFM in\\r\\nCAD and advanced modeling techniques.\",\"Week 5\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: explanation and live software demonstration of advanced part\\r\\nmodeling features (sweep, loft, shell, patterns, ribs) with practical\\r\\nexamples.,Hands-on Laboratory Work: Guided exercises in CAD\\r\\nsoftware to practice creating complex parts and simple\\r\\nassemblies.,Group Problem-Solving: Students work in small groups\\r\\nto collaboratively design a part requiring speci\\ufb01c advanced features,\\r\\ndiscussing optimal modeling strategies. OFF-SITE: tutorials on advanced CAD features and basic assembly work\\ufb02ows\\r\\n(e.g., speci\\ufb01c SolidWorks\\/Fusion 360\\/CATIA tutorials).,Online\\r\\nReading: Review digital textbook chapters or articles on advanced\\r\\nmodeling techniques, design intent, and assembly strategies.,LMS\\r\\nPractice Quizzes: Self-assessment quizzes on advanced feature\\r\\nde\\ufb01nitions and their applications.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n\'CAD\\/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' by P.N. Rao\\r\\n(or similar contemporary texts).,Software: Industry-standard CAD\\r\\nsoftware (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Fusion 360, PTC Creo, CATIA)\\r\\ninstalled in lab or accessible via student licenses.,Slides: Detailed\\r\\npresentation slides illustrating advanced modeling commands and\\r\\nassembly principles.,Video URL: Links to o\\ufb03cial software tutorials\\r\\nand reputable YouTube channels demonstrating advanced CAD\\r\\nfeatures (e.g., \'SolidWorks Advanced Part Modeling Tutorial\', \'Fusion\\r\\n360 Assembly Basics\').,Online Resources: Manufacturer\'s\\r\\ndocumentation for CAD software, CAD community forums,\\r\\nengineering design blogs.\",\"Week 6\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nPrelim Exam\",\"Week 7\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: GD&T standards (e.g., ASME Y14.5) and best practices. 2. Hands-on\\r\\nCAD laboratory session focusing on applying GD&T features in\\r\\ndesign software. 3. Group problem-solving exercises interpreting\\r\\nand correcting GD&T errors in sample drawings. OFF-SITE: advanced GD&T concepts and applications (e.g., speci\\ufb01c tolerance\\r\\ntypes). 2. Online reading assignments on the latest GD&T standards\\r\\nand industry trends. 3. Participate in an online discussion forum\\r\\naddressing challenges and solutions in GD&T implementation.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n\'Geometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing for Design, Manufacturing,\\r\\nand Inspection\' (e.g., by James D. Meadows). 2. CAD Software (e.g.,\\r\\nSolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, Fusion 360) with GD&T\\r\\nfunctionalities. 3. Lecture slides and notes on GD&T principles,\\r\\nsymbols, and rules. 4. Online resources: ASME Y14.5 standard\\r\\nexcerpts, industry whitepapers on GD&T, YouTube tutorials on CAD\\r\\nGD&T application. 5. Sample industrial engineering drawings with\\r\\nGD&T speci\\ufb01cations.\",\"Week 8\":\"Activities: ON-SITE:  OFF-SITE: simulation and analysis,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nSoftware (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, CATIA) with advanced\\r\\nmodules,Lecture slides on advanced surfacing and assembly,Video\\r\\ntutorials for speci\\ufb01c CAD commands and techniques,Textbook\\r\\nchapters on advanced CAD modeling,Online resources for assembly\\r\\nsimulation and analysis\",\"Week 9\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: technologies, and work\\ufb02ow integration. Hands-on CAD laboratory\\r\\nsession focusing on designing for AM (e.g., using generative design\\r\\ntools, lattice features, or preparing models for slicing). Case Study\\r\\nAnalysis and Group Presentation on real-world AM applications and\\r\\nchallenges. OFF-SITE: technologies (e.g., FDM, SLA, SLM) and dedicated slicing software.\\r\\nOnline Reading materials on topology optimization, lattice structure\\r\\ngeneration, and AM standards. Participate in an LMS discussion\\r\\nforum on the ethical implications and future trends of AM in\\r\\nmanufacturing.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nchapters on Additive Manufacturing, Rapid Prototyping, and Digital\\r\\nManufacturing. CAD Software with Generative Design\\/Topology\\r\\nOptimization modules (e.g., Autodesk Fusion 360, SolidWorks,\\r\\nnTopology, Netfabb). Slicing Software (e.g., Ultimaker Cura,\\r\\nSimplify3D, PrusaSlicer, speci\\ufb01c machine software). Academic\\r\\npapers and industry reports on AM applications and design\\r\\nguidelines. Video URLs: \'Introduction to 3D Printing Technologies\',\\r\\n\'Designing for Additive Manufacturing\', \'Topology Optimization\\r\\nExplained\', \'Additive Manufacturing Work\\ufb02ow\'. Lecture slides and\\r\\nsupplementary notes.\",\"Week 10\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: methodologies and Multi-axis kinematics; Hands-on CAD\\/CAM\\r\\nSoftware Lab Session (e.g., Mastercam, NX CAM, Fusion 360) for\\r\\nmulti-axis toolpath programming; Demonstrations of advanced\\r\\ntoolpath generation and simulation; Collaborative problem-solving\\r\\nfor optimizing machining strategies. OFF-SITE: features and multi-axis programming techniques; Online reading\\r\\nmaterials (academic papers, industry articles) on high-performance\\r\\nmachining and advanced toolpath optimization; Participation in an\\r\\nonline discussion forum on challenges and best practices in multi-\\r\\naxis machining; Self-paced practice exercises using CAD\\/CAM\\r\\nsoftware.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nchapters on Advanced CAM and Multi-axis Machining; CAD\\/CAM\\r\\nsoftware manuals and help documentation (e.g., Mastercam, NX\\r\\nCAM, Fusion 360 user guides); Online resources from software\\r\\nvendors (e.g., Autodesk, Siemens PLM, CNC Software Inc.); Academic\\r\\njournals on manufacturing engineering and advanced machining;\\r\\nVideo tutorials on advanced CAM strategies (e.g., YouTube channels\\r\\nof software providers, NCMT); Sample multi-axis CAD models for\\r\\npractice.\",\"Week 11\":\"Activities: ON-SITE:  OFF-SITE: documentation and tutorials (e.g., Siemens NX Learn, Mastercam\\r\\nUniversity), YouTube channels (e.g., Haas Automation, Mazak, DMG\\r\\nMori); Academic Papers: IEEE, ASME, CIRP publications on advanced\\r\\nmanufacturing and multi-axis machining; Instructor-prepared lecture\\r\\nslides, lab manuals, and sample CAD models for multi-axis parts.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\n\'Computer-Aided Manufacturing\' by Tien-Chien Chang, Richard A.\\r\\nWysk, Hsu-Pin Wang (relevant chapters on advanced CAM);\\r\\nCAD\\/CAM Software: Siemens NX CAM, Mastercam, CATIA V5\\/V6 (with\\r\\nmulti-axis modules installed); Online Resources: O\\ufb03cial software\\r\\ndocumentation and tutorials (e.g., Siemens NX Learn, Mastercam\\r\\nUniversity), YouTube channels (e.g., Haas Automation, Mazak, DMG\\r\\nMori); Academic Papers: IEEE, ASME, CIRP publications on advanced\\r\\nmanufacturing and multi-axis machining; Instructor-prepared lecture\\r\\nslides, lab manuals, and sample CAD models for multi-axis parts.\",\"Week 12\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nMidterm Exam\",\"Week 13\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: axis kinematics and advanced toolpath types. 2. CAD\\/CAM Software\\r\\nHands-on Lab: Guided exercises on 4-axis and 5-axis toolpath\\r\\ncreation and simulation. 3. Demonstration: Live software\\r\\ndemonstration of advanced CAM features and collision detection. 4.\\r\\nGroup Discussion: Pros and cons of di\\ufb00erent advanced CAM\\r\\nstrategies in speci\\ufb01c manufacturing contexts. OFF-SITE: tutorials on advanced CAM features (e.g., Autodesk Fusion 360,\\r\\nMastercam, SolidCAM). 2. Online Reading: Articles and white papers\\r\\non High-Speed Machining, Adaptive Clearing, and multi-axis\\r\\napplications. 3. LMS Forum Discussion: Share insights on industry\\r\\ntrends and challenges in multi-axis machining. 4. Simulation\\r\\nPractice: Independent practice on generating and verifying multi-\\r\\naxis toolpaths and advanced strategies in CAD\\/CAM software.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nChapters: Advanced CAM, Multi-axis Machining. 2. CAD\\/CAM\\r\\nSoftware (e.g., Fusion 360, Mastercam, SolidCAM, CATIA, Siemens\\r\\nNX). 3. Instructor-prepared slides and lab manuals for multi-axis\\r\\nmachining. 4. Video Tutorials: e.g., \'5-Axis Machining Fundamentals\'\\r\\n(YouTube), \'Adaptive Clearing Explained\' (Software vendor\\r\\nchannels). 5. Technical Papers\\/Articles on High-Speed Machining and\\r\\nmulti-axis applications. 6. Sample 3D models for multi-axis\\r\\nmachining exercises.\",\"Week 14\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: techniques (e.g., 5-axis machining, feature-based machining, high-\\r\\nspeed machining); Laboratory Session: Hands-on exploration of\\r\\nCAD\\/CAM software for robot programming and simulation; Group\\r\\nDiscussion: Challenges and opportunities in CAD\\/CAM integration\\r\\nwith Industry 4.0 technologies. OFF-SITE: robotic manufacturing cells and automated production lines (e.g.,\\r\\nautomotive, aerospace); Online Reading: Research papers or articles\\r\\non advanced CAM algorithms, human-robot collaboration, and digital\\r\\ntwins in manufacturing; LMS Quiz: Conceptual understanding of\\r\\nadvanced CAM and automation integration.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nGroover, M. P. (2020). *Fundamentals of Modern Manufacturing:\\r\\nMaterials, Processes, and Systems*. (Relevant chapters on\\r\\nautomation, robotics, and advanced CAM); Software: Siemens NX\\r\\nCAM, CATIA, SolidWorks CAM, Mastercam (with advanced modules\\r\\nfor multi-axis machining and robot simulation); Video URL: Industry\\r\\n4.0 manufacturing facility tours, robotic welding\\/assembly\\r\\ndemonstrations (e.g., KUKA, FANUC educational videos); Online\\r\\nArticles: Peer-reviewed journals on advanced manufacturing\\r\\nautomation (e.g., IEEE Xplore, ScienceDirect); Lecture Slides:\\r\\n\'Advanced CAM and Robotics Integration.\'\",\"Week 15\":\"Activities: ON-SITE:  OFF-SITE: advanced software features.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nGuidelines and Rubrics; Advanced CAD\\/CAM Software (e.g.,\\r\\nSolidWorks, CATIA, Siemens NX, Fusion 360, Mastercam); Academic\\r\\npapers and industry whitepapers on Industry 4.0, IoT in\\r\\nmanufacturing, and smart factories; Case studies of integrated\\r\\nCAD\\/CAM systems in advanced manufacturing; Online tutorials for\\r\\nadvanced software features.\",\"Week 16\":\"Activities: ON-SITE: and Peer Feedback Session; Moderated Discussion on project\\r\\nchallenges and solutions. OFF-SITE: Preparation of Presentation Materials; Review of Peer Feedback and\\r\\nSelf-Re\\ufb02ection.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nComprehensive CAD\\/CAM software suites (e.g., SolidWorks, CATIA,\\r\\nFusion 360, Mastercam, Siemens NX); Project guidelines and rubrics;\\r\\nOnline academic resources for advanced manufacturing case\\r\\nstudies; Presentation software and audiovisual equipment.\",\"Week 17\":\"Activities: ON-SITE:  OFF-SITE: from Deloitte, McKinsey, World Economic Forum on Industry 4.0 and\\r\\nfuture manufacturing.,, Learning and Teaching Support Materials:\\r\\nChapter: \'Industry 4.0 and Advanced Manufacturing\'; Academic\\r\\nPapers\\/Journals on Digital Twins, IoT in Manufacturing, AI in Design\\r\\nAutomation; Video URLs: Siemens Digital Enterprise Suite overview,\\r\\nDassault Syst\\u00e8mes 3DEXPERIENCE platform; Simulation Software\\r\\n(e.g., Ansys, Abaqus for advanced analysis concepts); Online articles\\r\\nfrom Deloitte, McKinsey, World Economic Forum on Industry 4.0 and\\r\\nfuture manufacturing.\",\"Week 18\":\"Detailed Lesson Content:\\r\\nFinal Exam\"}',NULL,3,NULL,NULL,'The Bachelor of Science in Manufacturing Engineering (BSMfgE) is a multidisciplinary program focusing on designing, optimizing, and\r\nmanaging production processes, materials, and systems. It prepares students to improve eﬃciency, quality, and automation from product\r\ndesign to ﬁnal assembly, combining engineering principles with management techniques',NULL,NULL,'The Bachelor of Science in Manufacturing Engineering (BSMfgE) program is designed to produce graduates capable of designing, optimizing,\r\nand managing production systems, materials, and processes','A Bachelor of Science in Manufacturing Engineering (BSMfgE) is designed to produce graduates capable of designing, optimizing, and\r\nmanaging complex production systems and processes. The Course Intended Learning Outcomes (CILOs)—often termed Program Outcomes\r\n(POs) or Student Outcomes (SOs)—typically align with industry standards like ABET, focusing on technical competence, design, and\r\nprofessional responsibility.','based teaching and learning (OBTL) is an approach where\r\nteaching and learning activities are developed to support the learning\r\noutcomes. It is a student-centered approach for the delivery of\r\neducational programs where the curriculum topics in a program and the\r\ncourses contained in it are expressed as the intended outcomes for\r\nstudents to learn. It is an approach in which teachers facilitate and\r\nstudents ﬁnd themselves actively engaged in their learning.\r\nIts primary focus is the clear statement of what students should be able\r\nto do after taking a course, known as the Intended Learning Outcomes\r\n(ILOs). The ILOs describe what the learners will be able to do when they\r\nhave completed their course or program. These are statements, written\r\nfrom the students\' perspective, indicating the level of understanding and\r\nperformance they are expected to achieve as a result of engaging in\r\nteaching and learning experience. Once the ILOs have been determined,\r\nthe next step in OBTL is to design the Teaching / Learning Activities\r\n(TLAs) which require students to actively participate in the construction of\r\ntheir new knowledge and abilities. A TLA is any activity which stimulates,\r\nencourages or facilitates learning of one or more intended learning\r\noutcome. The ﬁnal OBTL component is the Assessment Tasks (ATs),\r\nwhich measure how well students can use their new abilities to solve realworld problems, design, demonstrate creativity, and communicate\r\neﬀectively, among others. An AT can be any method of assessing how\r\nwell a set of ILO has been achieved.','Curtis, M. Handbook of Dimensional Measurement. Industrial Press, Inc.; 5 edition, \r\n2013.\r\nDotson, C. Fundamentals of Dimensional Metrology. Delmar Cengage Learning: 6 edition,\r\n\r\n2015.\r\nKochsiek, Manfred and Michael Glaser. Handbook of Metrology, \r\n2010.','BCP Learning Management System (LMS):\r\nhttps://bcpeducollege.elearningcommons.com/login/index.php\r\nOnline Resources: YouTube, etc.','Student must be able to:\r\n\r\n1. complete at least 80% of student participation;\r\n\r\n2. demonstrate punctuality according to his/her schedule; and,\r\n\r\n3. accomplish alternative assessment (if needed)\r\n\r\n3.\r\n1. when student fail to comply or perform poorly in a major examination\r\nand/or non-participation because of valid reason e.g. health, force majeure\r\nneeds to\r\nprovide alternative assessment such as project, presentation, oral\r\nexamination, and research output','Cluster Leader:\r\nMs. Eliza O. Gomba, LPT\r\nMember:\r\nMs. Divine Grace S. Rapsing, LPT','Cluster Leader:\r\nMs. Eliza O. Gomba, LPT\r\nEmail Address: missyelayg.bcps@gmail.com\r\nConsultation Hours:\r\nMonday-Thursday, 3-5PM\r\nTime and Venue: General Education Oﬃce\r\nFaculty Member:\r\nMs. Divine Grace Rapsing\r\nEmail Address: rapsingdivine.12@gmail.com\r\nConsultation Hours:\r\nMonday, 1PM-7PM\r\nTime and Venue: CRAD Oﬃce\r\nGRADING SYSTEM\r\nGrade Component	Percentage (%)\r\nPrelim	30%\r\nClass Standing	40%\r\nAttendance (F2F)	7%\r\nAttendance (Online)	3%\r\nWritten Works (F2F)	27%\r\nWritten Works (Online)	13%\r\nPerformance Task (F2F)	33%\r\nPerformance Task (Online)	17%\r\nProject	30%\r\nMajor Examination	30%\r\n\r\nGrade Component	Percentage (%)\r\nMidterm	30%\r\nClass Standing	40%\r\nAttendance (F2F)	7%\r\nAttendance (Online)	3%\r\nWritten Works (F2F)	27%\r\nWritten Works (Online)	13%\r\nPerformance Task (F2F)	33%\r\nPerformance Task (Online)	17%\r\nProject	30%\r\nMajor Examination	30%\r\nFinals	40%\r\nClass Standing	40%\r\nAttendance (F2F)	7%\r\nAttendance (Online)	3%\r\nWritten Works (F2F)	27%\r\nWritten Works (Online)	13%\r\nPerformance Task (F2F)	33%\r\nPerformance Task (Online)	17%\r\nProject	30%\r\nMajor Examination	30%','Lecture Slides andHandouts on Geometric and Dimensional Constraints. 4. Online CADTutorials (e.g., YouTube channels, LinkedIn Learning, software-speciﬁc forums). 5. CAD software\'s built-in help documentation andtutorials.Output Materials: 1. Completed CAD ﬁles (.prt, .sldprt, .f3d, .dwg,etc.) from the hands-on lab exercise. 2. Quiz Answer Sheet onconstraint types. 3. Completed CAD ﬁles (.prt, .sldprt, .f3d, .dwg,etc.) for the homework assignment. 4. Contributions to the onlinediscussion forum.Week 4Content: Parametric and Feature-Based Modeling for Complex Parts- Advanced Sketching Tools and Techniques (Splines, Patterns,Mirroring) - Complex Solid Modeling Features (Sweeps, Lofts, Shell,Ribs, Draft) - Design Intent and Parametric Relationships -Introduction to Design for Manufacturability (DFM) considerations inCADStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Apply advancedsketching and feature-based modeling tools (e.g., sweeps, lofts,shells) to construct complex 3D components. 2. Implementparametric relationships and design intent to create adaptable andmodiﬁable 3D models. 3. Evaluate the impact of diﬀerent modelingstrategies on design ﬂexibility and potential manufacturingprocesses.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: 1. Practical Lab Exercise: Modeling a complex mechanicalcomponent with speciﬁed features and parametric requirements. 2.Short Quiz: On advanced CAD features, design intent, and basic DFMprinciples.OFFSITE: 1. Design Challenge: Model a given complex industrialpart, ensuring parametric control and submitting the CAD ﬁle alongwith a brief design report. 2. Online Forum Discussion: Contribute toa discussion on \'Challenges and best practices in modeling complexgeometries for manufacturing\'.Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): 1. Lecture-Demonstration: Instructor-leddemonstration of advanced sketching and solid modeling features(e.g., sweeps, lofts, shells, ribs, drafts). 2. Hands-on LaboratorySession: Guided practice exercises on applying parametric designand complex feature creation using CAD software. 3. GroupDiscussion: Analyzing case studies of complex parts and discussingDFM considerations during their design.Online (Oﬀ-Site): 1. Video Tutorials: Watch curated video tutorialson speciﬁc advanced CAD functions (e.g., \'Mastering the LoftCommand\', \'Parametric Design Strategies\'). 2. Online Reading:Review articles and white papers on design intent, parametricmodeling best practices, and introductory DFM guidelines. 3. LMSQuiz: Complete an online quiz assessing understanding of advancedmodeling concepts and parametric design principles.Week 4Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): 1. Textbook:\'CAD/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' (e.g., byIbrahim Zeid or similar industry-standard texts). 2. Software: Latestversions of industry-standard CAD software (e.g., SolidWorks,Autodesk Inventor, CATIA, PTC Creo) with academic licenses. 3.Lecture Slides: Visual aids detailing advanced features andparametric design workﬂows. 4. Video Tutorials: Links to reputableonline CAD tutorial platforms (e.g., SolidWorks oﬃcial tutorials,YouTube channels). 5. Online Articles/Journals: Resources on DFM inCAD and advanced modeling techniques.Output Materials: 1. CAD Part Files (.SLDPRT, .IPT, .CATPart) ofcomplex components. 2. Short Design Report detailing parametricstrategy and DFM considerations. 3. Completed Lab Worksheets. 4.Quiz results (on-site and oﬀ-site). 5. Online Forum contributions.Week 5Content: Advanced Part Modeling Techniques and Introduction toAssembly DesignStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: Apply advanced partmodeling features such as sweeps, lofts, shells, ribs, and patterns tocreate complex 3D geometries.,Analyze the appropriate use casesfor diﬀerent advanced modeling techniques in manufacturing designscenarios.,Demonstrate the ability to create basic productassemblies using standard mating and constraint techniques (e.g.,coincident, concentric, parallel, perpendicular).Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Practical CAD Lab Exercise: Design and model a complexcomponent requiring advanced features (e.g., a bottle, a turbineblade segment, a complex bracket).,Short Quiz: Identiﬁcation andapplication of advanced modeling features and basic assemblyconcepts.OFFSITE: Individual Design Project: Create a 3D model of aspeciﬁed industrial part using at least three advanced modelingtechniques and assemble it with a simple matingcomponent.,Research and Report: Investigate the industryapplications of advanced surfacing or solid modeling techniques in achosen manufacturing sector (e.g., automotive, aerospace,consumer electronics).Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Lecture-Demonstration: In-depthexplanation and live software demonstration of advanced partmodeling features (sweep, loft, shell, patterns, ribs) with practicalexamples.,Hands-on Laboratory Work: Guided exercises in CADsoftware to practice creating complex parts and simpleassemblies.,Group Problem-Solving: Students work in small groupsto collaboratively design a part requiring speciﬁc advanced features,discussing optimal modeling strategies.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Video Watching: Access curated online videotutorials on advanced CAD features and basic assembly workﬂows(e.g., speciﬁc SolidWorks/Fusion 360/CATIA tutorials).,OnlineReading: Review digital textbook chapters or articles on advancedmodeling techniques, design intent, and assembly strategies.,LMSPractice Quizzes: Self-assessment quizzes on advanced featuredeﬁnitions and their applications.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): Textbook:\'CAD/CAM: Computer-Aided Design and Manufacturing\' by P.N. Rao(or similar contemporary texts).,Software: Industry-standard CADsoftware (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Fusion 360, PTC Creo, CATIA)installed in lab or accessible via student licenses.,Slides: Detailedpresentation slides illustrating advanced modeling commands andassembly principles.,Video URL: Links to oﬃcial software tutorialsand reputable YouTube channels demonstrating advanced CADfeatures (e.g., \'SolidWorks Advanced Part Modeling Tutorial\', \'Fusion360 Assembly Basics\').,Online Resources: Manufacturer\'sdocumentation for CAD software, CAD community forums,engineering design blogs.Output Materials: CAD Part Files (.SLDPRT, .F3D, .CATPart, .PRT)demonstrating complex geometries.,CAD Assembly Files (.SLDASM,.F3Z, .CATProduct, .ASM) for basic product assemblies.,ShortResearch Report/Documentation (PDF) on industry applications ofadvanced modeling, including screenshots of models.Week 6Prelim ExamWeek 7Content: Geometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing (GD&T)Principles and Applications in CAD - Review of traditionaldimensioning and tolerancing limitations. - Introduction to GD&Tconcepts: feature control frames, datums, form, orientation,location, runout, and proﬁle tolerances. - GD&T symbols and theirinterpretation (e.g., ASME Y14.5 standard). - Importance of GD&T inmanufacturing for quality control, interchangeability, and assembly.- Practical application of GD&T in CAD software for part design andassembly.Student Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Explain thefundamental principles and symbols of Geometric Dimensioning andTolerancing (GD&T). 2. Interpret engineering drawings thatincorporate GD&T speciﬁcations eﬀectively. 3. Apply appropriateGD&T features to CAD models to ensure design intent,manufacturing accuracy, and functionality. 4. Evaluate the impact ofGD&T on product quality, assembly eﬃciency, and cost-eﬀectiveness in modern manufacturing processes.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: 1. Quiz on GD&T symbols, deﬁnitions, and interpretation.2. Practical CAD exercise: Applying GD&T to a given mechanicalcomponent model within CAD software.OFFSITE: 1. Analysis of an industrial engineering drawingcontaining complex GD&T speciﬁcations. 2. Research and present ashort report on a case study where GD&T signiﬁcantly improved amanufacturing process or product quality.Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): 1. Interactive lecture and discussion onGD&T standards (e.g., ASME Y14.5) and best practices. 2. Hands-onCAD laboratory session focusing on applying GD&T features indesign software. 3. Group problem-solving exercises interpretingand correcting GD&T errors in sample drawings.Online (Oﬀ-Site): 1. Watch curated instructional videos onadvanced GD&T concepts and applications (e.g., speciﬁc tolerancetypes). 2. Online reading assignments on the latest GD&T standardsand industry trends. 3. Participate in an online discussion forumaddressing challenges and solutions in GD&T implementation.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): 1. Textbook:\'Geometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing for Design, Manufacturing,and Inspection\' (e.g., by James D. Meadows). 2. CAD Software (e.g.,SolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, Fusion 360) with GD&Tfunctionalities. 3. Lecture slides and notes on GD&T principles,symbols, and rules. 4. Online resources: ASME Y14.5 standardexcerpts, industry whitepapers on GD&T, YouTube tutorials on CADGD&T application. 5. Sample industrial engineering drawings withGD&T speciﬁcations.Output Materials: 1. Completed CAD models with correctly appliedGD&T features, demonstrating design intent. 2. Quiz resultsdemonstrating understanding of GD&T concepts. 3. Written analysisreport of an industrial drawing with GD&T speciﬁcations. 4. Shortresearch report on a GD&T case study in manufacturing.Week 8Content: Advanced CAD Modeling Techniques and Assemblies Student Intended Learning Outcomes: Apply advancedsurfacing techniques (e.g., lofts, sweeps, boundary surfaces) tocreate complex geometric shapes for product design.,Construct andmanage multi-part assemblies using appropriate mating conditionsand assembly constraints.,Analyze the kinematic behavior of simpleassemblies to understand motion and interference.,Evaluate theimpact of diﬀerent modeling strategies on design intent anddownstream manufacturing processes.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Midterm Exam (Theory and Practical Application),Assembly Design ChallengeOFFSITE: Research paper on emerging CAD modeling trends (e.g.,generative design, parametric optimization), Individual assemblyproject reportSuggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Lecture on advanced surfacing andassembly techniques, Hands-on laboratory session for complexmodeling and assembly creation, Case study analysis of productassemblies, Peer review of assembly designsOnline (Oﬀ-Site): Online tutorials for advanced CAD features,Interactive simulation exercises for assembly kinematics, Readingassignments on assembly best practices and design formanufacturability (DFM)Week 8Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): CADSoftware (e.g., SolidWorks, Autodesk Inventor, CATIA) with advancedmodules,Lecture slides on advanced surfacing and assembly,Videotutorials for speciﬁc CAD commands and techniques,Textbookchapters on advanced CAD modeling,Online resources for assemblysimulation and analysisOutput Materials: Complex 3D CAD models of individual parts,Fully constrained multi-part assemblies, Assembly simulation results,Research paper on advanced CAD trends, Midterm Exam paperWeek 9Content: Introduction to Additive Manufacturing (AM) and itsIntegration with CAD/CAM Workﬂows: - Principles of AM (3D Printing)Technologies (e.g., FDM, SLA, SLM, SLS) - CAD for AM: Designconsiderations, advanced modeling techniques (e.g., latticestructures, generative design, topology optimization) - CAM for AM:Slicing software, support generation, build plate optimization,process parameters - Post-processing and quality control in AM -Applications of AM in Manufacturing Engineering (prototyping,tooling, functional parts, mass customization)Student Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Explain thefundamental principles and various technologies of AdditiveManufacturing (AM). 2. Analyze design considerations and advancedmodeling techniques (e.g., lattice structures, topology optimization)speciﬁcally for AM using CAD software. 3. Apply CAM principles forAM, including slicing, support generation, and build orientationoptimization. 4. Evaluate the advantages and limitations ofintegrating AM into traditional manufacturing workﬂows. 5. Proposesuitable AM processes for speciﬁc manufacturing engineeringapplications based on design requirements and material properties.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Short Quiz on AM principles and CAD for AM concepts.Group Discussion and Presentation on case studies of AMapplications in diﬀerent industries.OFFSITE: Design an AM-optimized component (e.g., lightweightbracket with lattice structure or topology-optimized part) using CADsoftware, submitting the CAD ﬁle and a brief design justiﬁcationreport. Research paper on a speciﬁc AM technology\'s impact on achosen manufacturing industry, including its CAD/CAM integrationchallenges and solutions.Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Interactive Lecture on AM principles,technologies, and workﬂow integration. Hands-on CAD laboratorysession focusing on designing for AM (e.g., using generative designtools, lattice features, or preparing models for slicing). Case StudyAnalysis and Group Presentation on real-world AM applications andchallenges.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Watch curated video tutorials on speciﬁc AMtechnologies (e.g., FDM, SLA, SLM) and dedicated slicing software.Online Reading materials on topology optimization, lattice structuregeneration, and AM standards. Participate in an LMS discussionforum on the ethical implications and future trends of AM inmanufacturing.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): Textbookchapters on Additive Manufacturing, Rapid Prototyping, and DigitalManufacturing. CAD Software with Generative Design/TopologyOptimization modules (e.g., Autodesk Fusion 360, SolidWorks,nTopology, Netfabb). Slicing Software (e.g., Ultimaker Cura,Simplify3D, PrusaSlicer, speciﬁc machine software). Academicpapers and industry reports on AM applications and designguidelines. Video URLs: \'Introduction to 3D Printing Technologies\',\'Designing for Additive Manufacturing\', \'Topology OptimizationExplained\', \'Additive Manufacturing Workﬂow\'. Lecture slides andsupplementary notes.Output Materials: Quiz Answer Sheet. Group DiscussionSummary/Presentation Slides. CAD Model ﬁle (.STL, .STEP, or nativeformat) of an AM-optimized component. Brief Design JustiﬁcationReport (PDF). Research Paper on AM technology\'s impact onmanufacturing.Week 10Content: Advanced CAM Strategies and Multi-axis Machining Student Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Evaluate variousadvanced CAM strategies (e.g., high-speed machining, adaptivemachining, trochoidal milling) for complex part manufacturing. 2.Apply multi-axis machining techniques (e.g., 4-axis, 5-axissimultaneous) to generate optimized toolpaths for intricategeometries. 3. Analyze the impact of advanced CAM parameters onmachining eﬃciency, surface ﬁnish, and tool life. 4. Propose suitablemulti-axis machining solutions for speciﬁc manufacturing challengesbased on part complexity and material properties.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Practical Lab Exercise: Multi-axis Toolpath Generation;Short Quiz on Advanced CAM Concepts and Terminology; GroupDiscussion on Multi-axis Machining Applications.OFFSITE: Case Study Analysis: Industrial Application of AdvancedCAM; Simulation Report on a Multi-axis Machining Project; Researchon Post-processing for 5-axis CNC Machines.Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Interactive Lecture on Advanced CAMmethodologies and Multi-axis kinematics; Hands-on CAD/CAMSoftware Lab Session (e.g., Mastercam, NX CAM, Fusion 360) formulti-axis toolpath programming; Demonstrations of advancedtoolpath generation and simulation; Collaborative problem-solvingfor optimizing machining strategies.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Online video tutorials on speciﬁc advanced CAMfeatures and multi-axis programming techniques; Online readingmaterials (academic papers, industry articles) on high-performancemachining and advanced toolpath optimization; Participation in anonline discussion forum on challenges and best practices in multi-axis machining; Self-paced practice exercises using CAD/CAMsoftware.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): Textbookchapters on Advanced CAM and Multi-axis Machining; CAD/CAMsoftware manuals and help documentation (e.g., Mastercam, NXCAM, Fusion 360 user guides); Online resources from softwarevendors (e.g., Autodesk, Siemens PLM, CNC Software Inc.); Academicjournals on manufacturing engineering and advanced machining;Video tutorials on advanced CAM strategies (e.g., YouTube channelsof software providers, NCMT); Sample multi-axis CAD models forpractice.Output Materials: Generated multi-axis toolpaths and associatedNC ﬁles; Detailed simulation reports of machining operations;Completed quiz on advanced CAM; Written case study analysisreport; Research summary on post-processing for 5-axis machines.Week 11Content: Advanced CAM Programming and Simulation: Multi-AxisMachining - Introduction to Multi-Axis Machining (3-axis vs. 4-axis vs.5-axis) - Kinematics and Tool Orientations in Multi-Axis Machining -Advanced Toolpath Strategies for Multi-Axis Operations (e.g., Swarf,Flowline, Contour) - Collision Detection and Avoidance in Multi-AxisSimulation - Post-Processing for Multi-Axis CNC Machines -Optimization Techniques for Multi-Axis ToolpathsStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Analyze the principlesand applications of 4-axis and 5-axis machining in complexmanufacturing scenarios. 2. Develop advanced CAM programs formulti-axis parts using specialized software features. 3. Performcomprehensive simulations of multi-axis machining processes toidentify and resolve potential issues like collisions and gouges. 4.Evaluate various multi-axis toolpath strategies for eﬃciency, surfacequality, and material removal rates. 5. Generate and interpret post-processed G-code for multi-axis CNC machines.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Practical Lab Exam: Multi-Axis CAM Programming andSimulation (Students program and simulate a complex 4/5-axis part).OFFSITE: Multi-Axis Machining Case Study Report (Students analyzea real-world application of multi-axis machining and propose anoptimized CAM strategy).Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Interactive Lecture: Principles andApplications of Multi-Axis Machining; Hands-on Laboratory Session:Multi-Axis CAM Software Proﬁciency (e.g., generating toolpaths for aturbine blade or impeller); Live Demonstration: Advanced SimulationFeatures and Collision Detection.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Curated Video Tutorials on Speciﬁc Multi-AxisCAM Software Modules; Online Reading: Research papers andindustry articles on the latest trends in 5-axis machining; LMS-basedDiscussion Forum: Challenges and solutions in multi-axis post-processing.Week 11Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): Textbook:\'Computer-Aided Manufacturing\' by Tien-Chien Chang, Richard A.Wysk, Hsu-Pin Wang (relevant chapters on advanced CAM);CAD/CAM Software: Siemens NX CAM, Mastercam, CATIA V5/V6 (withmulti-axis modules installed); Online Resources: Oﬃcial softwaredocumentation and tutorials (e.g., Siemens NX Learn, MastercamUniversity), YouTube channels (e.g., Haas Automation, Mazak, DMGMori); Academic Papers: IEEE, ASME, CIRP publications on advancedmanufacturing and multi-axis machining; Instructor-prepared lectureslides, lab manuals, and sample CAD models for multi-axis parts.Output Materials: Completed Multi-Axis CAM Program Files (.NC,.APT, or native CAM ﬁle); Detailed Multi-Axis Machining SimulationReport (including collision analysis, cycle time, and material removalrate); Written Case Study Report on Multi-Axis MachiningApplication.Week 12Midterm ExamWeek 13Content: Multi-axis Machining and Advanced CAM Strategies Student Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Analyze theapplications and beneﬁts of multi-axis machining in complex partmanufacturing. 2. Generate multi-axis toolpaths using CAD/CAMsoftware for speciﬁc part geometries. 3. Evaluate and optimizeadvanced CAM strategies (e.g., High-Speed Machining, AdaptiveClearing) to improve machining eﬃciency and surface quality. 4.Identify and mitigate potential collisions in multi-axis machiningsimulations.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: 1. Practical Lab Exam: Multi-axis toolpath generation andsimulation. 2. Group Problem-Solving Activity: Optimizing a multi-axis machining scenario.OFFSITE: 1. Case Study Analysis: Research and report on anindustry application of 5-axis machining. 2. CAM Project Part 3:Develop and simulate advanced CAM strategies for a complex part(e.g., impeller, turbine blade).Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): 1. Interactive Lecture: Principles of multi-axis kinematics and advanced toolpath types. 2. CAD/CAM SoftwareHands-on Lab: Guided exercises on 4-axis and 5-axis toolpathcreation and simulation. 3. Demonstration: Live softwaredemonstration of advanced CAM features and collision detection. 4.Group Discussion: Pros and cons of diﬀerent advanced CAMstrategies in speciﬁc manufacturing contexts.Online (Oﬀ-Site): 1. Video Tutorials: Watch manufacturer-speciﬁctutorials on advanced CAM features (e.g., Autodesk Fusion 360,Mastercam, SolidCAM). 2. Online Reading: Articles and white paperson High-Speed Machining, Adaptive Clearing, and multi-axisapplications. 3. LMS Forum Discussion: Share insights on industrytrends and challenges in multi-axis machining. 4. SimulationPractice: Independent practice on generating and verifying multi-axis toolpaths and advanced strategies in CAD/CAM software.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): 1. TextbookChapters: Advanced CAM, Multi-axis Machining. 2. CAD/CAMSoftware (e.g., Fusion 360, Mastercam, SolidCAM, CATIA, SiemensNX). 3. Instructor-prepared slides and lab manuals for multi-axismachining. 4. Video Tutorials: e.g., \'5-Axis Machining Fundamentals\'(YouTube), \'Adaptive Clearing Explained\' (Software vendorchannels). 5. Technical Papers/Articles on High-Speed Machining andmulti-axis applications. 6. Sample 3D models for multi-axismachining exercises.Output Materials: 1. Completed CAD/CAM software ﬁles with multi-axis toolpaths and advanced strategies (.f3d, .mcx, .sldprt, etc.). 2.Simulation reports/screenshots of toolpath veriﬁcation and collisionanalysis. 3. Case study report on multi-axis applications. 4. CAMProject Part 3 documentation (toolpath description, cuttingparameters, simulation results, optimization rationale).Week 14Content: Advanced CAM Strategies and Integration withManufacturing Systems (Robotics & Automation)Student Intended Learning Outcomes: Analyze the principlesand applications of advanced CAM strategies for complexgeometries and multi-axis machining; Evaluate the role of CAD/CAMin robotic programming and automated manufacturing cells; Designa basic integrated CAD/CAM-robotics workﬂow for a speciﬁcmanufacturing task; Propose solutions for optimizing manufacturingprocesses through CAD/CAM and automation integration.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Group Presentation: Case Study on Integrated CAD/CAM-Robotics in ManufacturingOFFSITE: Design and Simulation Project: Robotic Path Planning andCollision Avoidance using CAD/CAM DataSuggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Interactive Lecture: Advanced CAMtechniques (e.g., 5-axis machining, feature-based machining, high-speed machining); Laboratory Session: Hands-on exploration ofCAD/CAM software for robot programming and simulation; GroupDiscussion: Challenges and opportunities in CAD/CAM integrationwith Industry 4.0 technologies.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Video Watching: Case studies on advancedrobotic manufacturing cells and automated production lines (e.g.,automotive, aerospace); Online Reading: Research papers or articleson advanced CAM algorithms, human-robot collaboration, and digitaltwins in manufacturing; LMS Quiz: Conceptual understanding ofadvanced CAM and automation integration.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): Textbook:Groover, M. P. (2020). *Fundamentals of Modern Manufacturing:Materials, Processes, and Systems*. (Relevant chapters onautomation, robotics, and advanced CAM); Software: Siemens NXCAM, CATIA, SolidWorks CAM, Mastercam (with advanced modulesfor multi-axis machining and robot simulation); Video URL: Industry4.0 manufacturing facility tours, robotic welding/assemblydemonstrations (e.g., KUKA, FANUC educational videos); OnlineArticles: Peer-','journals on advanced manufacturingautomation (e.g., IEEE Xplore, ScienceDirect); Lecture Slides:\'Advanced CAM and Robotics Integration.\'Output Materials: Group Presentation Slides; Simulation Report(Robotic Path Planning); CAD/CAM Software Files (e.g., 5-axistoolpaths, robot cell layout, simulation results); LMS Quiz Results.Week 15Content: Advanced CAD/CAM Integration for Industry 4.0 and SmartManufacturing / Final Project Presentation and DefenseStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: Evaluate the role ofadvanced CAD/CAM systems in Industry 4.0 and smartmanufacturing environments; Demonstrate the ability to integratecomplex CAD designs with CAM strategies for automated production;Present and defend a comprehensive CAD/CAM project, showcasingdesign, simulation, and manufacturing planning; Propose innovativesolutions to manufacturing challenges leveraging integratedCAD/CAM technologies.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Final Project Presentation and Oral Defense; PeerEvaluation of Project Presentations.OFFSITE: Submission of Final Project Report; Submission ofCAD/CAM Project Portfolio (including models, simulations, andtoolpaths).Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Student-led Project Presentations; Q&Asessions and constructive feedback; Expert panel discussion (ifavailable) on Industry 4.0 applications of CAD/CAM; Peer reviewworkshops for project reports.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Review and reﬁnement of projectdocumentation; Collaborative online reﬁnement of project reportsand presentations; Research and analysis of current trends in smartmanufacturing and Industry 4.0; Online forum discussion on futuredirections of CAD/CAM.Week 15Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): ProjectGuidelines and Rubrics; Advanced CAD/CAM Software (e.g.,SolidWorks, CATIA, Siemens NX, Fusion 360, Mastercam); Academicpapers and industry whitepapers on Industry 4.0, IoT inmanufacturing, and smart factories; Case studies of integratedCAD/CAM systems in advanced manufacturing; Online tutorials foradvanced software features.Output Materials: Final CAD/CAM Project Report; ProjectPresentation Slides/Video; Complete CAD Models (native ﬁles); CAMToolpaths and Simulation Files; Manufacturing Process Plan; PeerEvaluation Forms.Week 16Content: Final Project Presentations: Integrated CAD/CAM SystemDesign and Manufacturing ImplementationStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Synthesize and applyadvanced CAD/CAM principles to design, simulate, and plan themanufacturing of a complex product. 2. Present a comprehensiveﬁnal project, eﬀectively communicating design rationale,manufacturing strategies, and achieved outcomes. 3. Defendtechnical choices and justify the economic and operational beneﬁtsof the proposed CAD/CAM solution.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Final Project Oral Presentation and Demonstration; Q&ASession with Instructors and Peers.OFFSITE: Submission of Comprehensive Final Project Report(including all supporting ﬁles).Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Student Project Presentations; Instructorand Peer Feedback Session; Moderated Discussion on projectchallenges and solutions.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Independent Final Project Reﬁnement;Preparation of Presentation Materials; Review of Peer Feedback andSelf-Reﬂection.Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM):Comprehensive CAD/CAM software suites (e.g., SolidWorks, CATIA,Fusion 360, Mastercam, Siemens NX); Project guidelines and rubrics;Online academic resources for advanced manufacturing casestudies; Presentation software and audiovisual equipment.Output Materials: Final Project Report (digital submission);Presentation Slides/Demonstration Files; CAD Model Files (e.g.,.SLDPRT, .STEP); CAM Toolpath Files (e.g., .NC, .G-code); SimulationResults (e.g., FEA reports, process simulations); Bill of of Materials(BOM).Week 17Content: Advanced Manufacturing Strategies and Industry 4.0Integration with CAD/CAMStudent Intended Learning Outcomes: 1. Analyze the impact ofIndustry 4.0 technologies (e.g., IoT, AI, Big Data, Cloud Computing)on CAD/CAM workﬂows and manufacturing processes. 2. Evaluateadvanced manufacturing strategies such as smart manufacturing,digital twins, and additive manufacturing for their integrationpotential with CAD/CAM systems. 3. Propose innovative solutions forreal-world manufacturing challenges by leveraging integratedCAD/CAM and Industry 4.0 concepts.Assessment Tasks (ATs):ONSITE: Group Presentation: \'Industry 4.0 Case Study and CAD/CAMIntegration Proposal\'OFFSITE: Research Paper: \'Future Trends in CAD/CAM, SmartManufacturing, and Cybersecurity\'Suggested Teaching/Learning Activities (TLAs):Face to Face (On-Site): Interactive Lecture on Industry 4.0 pillarsand their relevance to CAD/CAM; Case Study Analysis and GroupDiscussion on successful smart manufacturing implementations;Expert Guest Speaker (virtual or in-person) on Smart Factories andDigital Transformation.Online (Oﬀ-Site): Watch curated documentaries/webinars onSmart Manufacturing and Digital Twins; Online research on speciﬁcdigital twin applications in diﬀerent industries; Participate in an LMSforum discussion on the ethical implications and cybersecuritychallenges of AI in manufacturing.Week 17Learning and Teaching Support Materials (LTSM): TextbookChapter: \'Industry 4.0 and Advanced Manufacturing\'; AcademicPapers/Journals on Digital Twins, IoT in Manufacturing, AI in DesignAutomation; Video URLs: Siemens Digital Enterprise Suite overview,Dassault Systèmes 3DEXPERIENCE platform; Simulation Software(e.g., Ansys, Abaqus for advanced analysis concepts); Online articlesfrom Deloitte, McKinsey, World Economic Forum on Industry 4.0 andfuture manufacturing.Output Materials: Group Presentation Slides and Report;Comprehensive Research Paper; Discussion Forum Posts.Week 18Final ExamCOURSE REQUIREMENTS AND POLICIESBasic Readings / Textbooks: Curtis, M. Handbook of Dimensional Measurement. Industrial Press, Inc.; 5 edition, 2013.Dotson, C. Fundamentals of Dimensional Metrology. Delmar Cengage Learning: 6 edition,2015.Kochsiek, Manfred and Michael Glaser. Handbook of Metrology, 2010.Extended Readings /Extended Readings / References: BCP Learning Management System (LMS):https://bcpeducollege.elearningcommons.com/login/index.phpOnline Resources: YouTube, etc.Course Assessment:	Student must be able to:1. complete at least 80% of student participation;2. demonstrate punctuality according to his/her schedule; and,3. accomplish alternative assessment (if needed)3.1. when student fail to comply or perform poorly in a major examinationand/or non-participation because of valid reason e.g. health, force majeureneeds toprovide alternative assessment such as project, presentation, oralexamination, and research outputCommittee Members:	Cluster Leader:Ms. Eliza O. Gomba, LPTMember:Ms. Divine Grace S. Rapsing, LPTConsultation Schedule:	Cluster Leader:Ms. Eliza O. Gomba, LPTEmail Address: missyelayg.bcps@gmail.comConsultation Hours:Monday-Thursday, 3-5PMTime and Venue: General Education OﬃceFaculty Member:Ms. Divine Grace RapsingEmail Address: rapsingdivine.12@gmail.comConsultation Hours:Monday, 1PM-7PMTime and Venue: CRAD OﬃceGRADING SYSTEMGrade Component	Percentage (%)Prelim	30%Class Standing	40%Attendance (F2F)	7%Attendance (Online)	3%Written Works (F2F)	27%Written Works (Online)	13%Performance Task (F2F)	33%Performance Task (Online)	17%Project	30%Major Examination	30%Grade Component	Percentage (%)Midterm	30%Class Standing	40%Attendance (F2F)	7%Attendance (Online)	3%Written Works (F2F)	27%Written Works (Online)	13%Performance Task (F2F)	33%Performance Task (Online)	17%Project	30%Major Examination	30%Finals	40%Class Standing	40%Attendance (F2F)	7%Attendance (Online)	3%Written Works (F2F)	27%Written Works (Online)	13%Performance Task (F2F)	33%Performance Task (Online)	17%Project	30%Major Examination	30%Prepared:ELIZA O. GOMBA, LPTCluster LeaderReviewed:MICHAEL L. BERSAMIN, LPT','CHARLIE I. CARIÑO, Ph.D.Vice President for Academic Aﬀairs','2026-03-31 14:32:24','2026-03-31 14:32:24',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
insert  into `system_settings`(`id`,`category`,`key`,`value`,`description`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) values 
(1,'vision','school','BCP is committed to provide and promote quality education with a unique, modern and research-based curriculum with delivery systems geared towards excellence.','School Vision Statement','2026-02-05 18:22:53','2026-02-05 18:22:53'),
(2,'vision','dept_default','To improve the quality of student\'s input and by promoting IT enabled, market driven and internationally comparable programs through quality assurance systems, upgrading faculty qualifications and establishing international linkages.','Default Department Vision (for Professional Subjects)','2026-02-05 18:22:54','2026-02-05 18:22:54'),
(3,'vision','dept_general_education','BCP General Education Department innovates, investigates and discovers greatness and prosperity through oneness.','General Education Department Vision','2026-02-05 18:22:54','2026-02-05 18:22:54'),
(4,'mission','school','To produce self-motivated and self-directed individual who aims for academic excellence, God-fearing, peaceful, healthy and productive successful citizens.','School Mission Statement','2026-02-05 18:22:54','2026-02-05 18:22:54'),
(5,'mission','dept_default','The College of Computer Studies is committed to provide quality information and communication technology education through the use of modern and transformation learning teaching process.','Default Department Mission (for Professional Subjects)','2026-02-05 18:22:55','2026-02-05 18:22:55'),
(6,'mission','dept_general_education','To awaken the curiosity and ignite passion of individuals to excel independency in academic endeavors towards their development into ethically and morally strong people.','General Education Department Mission','2026-02-05 18:22:55','2026-02-05 18:22:55'),
(7,'philosophy','school','BCP advocates threefold core values: \"Fides\", \"Faith; \"Ratio\", Reason; Pax. Peace. \"Fides\" represents BCPs, endeavors for expansion, development, and growth amidst the challenges of the new millennium. \"Ratio\" symbolizes BCP\'s efforts to provide an education which can be man\'s tool to be liberated from all forms of ignorance and poverty. \"Pax\". BCP is a forerunner in the promotion of a harmonious relationship between the different sectors of its academic community.','School Philosophy','2026-02-05 18:22:56','2026-02-05 18:22:56'),
(8,'philosophy','dept_general_education','General Education advocates threefold core values \"Devotion\", \"Serenity\', \"Determination\" \"Devotion\" represents General Education commitment and dedication to provide quality education that will fuel the passion of the students for learning in driving academic success \"Serenity\" symbolizes a crucial element in the overall well-being and success of students by means of creating a more supportive, conducive, and enriching learning environment, enabling them to thrive academically, emotionally, and personally. \"Determination\" general education is committed to provide a high-quality, equitable, and supportive learning environment that empowers students to succeed.','General Education Department Philosophy','2026-02-05 18:22:56','2026-02-05 18:22:56'),
(9,'core_values','text','FAITH, KNOWLEDGE, CHARITY AND HUMILITY\nFAITH (Fides) represents BCP\'s endeavor for expansion, development and for growth amidst the global challenges of the new millennium.\nKNOWLEDGE (Cognito) connotes the institution\'s efforts to impart excellent lifelong education that can be used as human tool so that one can liberate himself/herself from ignorance and poverty\nCHARITY (Caritas) is the institution\'s commitment towards its clienteles.\nHUMILITY (Humiliates) refers to the institution\'s recognition of the human frailty, its imperfection.','BCP Core Values','2026-02-05 18:22:56','2026-02-05 18:22:56'),
(10,'legend','l','Facilitate Learning of the competencies','L - Facilitate Learning','2026-02-05 18:22:57','2026-02-05 18:22:57'),
(11,'legend','p','Allow student to practice competencies (No input but competency is evaluated)','P - Practice','2026-02-05 18:22:57','2026-02-05 18:22:57'),
(12,'legend','o','Provide opportunity for development (No input or evaluation, but there is opportunity to practice the competencies)','O - Opportunity','2026-02-05 18:22:57','2026-02-05 18:22:57'),
(13,'legend','ctpss','critical thinking and problem-solving skills','CTPSS Abbreviation','2026-02-05 18:22:58','2026-02-05 18:22:58'),
(14,'legend','ecc','effective communication and collaboration','ECC Abbreviation','2026-02-05 18:22:58','2026-02-05 18:22:58'),
(15,'legend','epp','ethical and professional practice','EPP Abbreviation','2026-02-05 18:22:58','2026-02-05 18:22:58'),
(16,'legend','glc','global and lifelong learning commitment','GLC Abbreviation','2026-02-05 18:22:59','2026-02-05 18:22:59'),
(17,'learning_outcomes','school_goals','BCP puts God in the center of all its efforts realize and operationalize its vision and missions through the following. Instruction, Research, Extension and Productivity','School Goals','2026-02-05 18:22:59','2026-02-05 18:22:59'),
(18,'learning_outcomes','program_goals','To cultivate a dynamic and inclusive learning environment that empowers students to become self-directed, ethical, and engaged citizens, equipped with the critical thinking, communication, and problem-solving skills necessary to thrive in a rapidly evolving world.','Program Goals','2026-02-05 18:23:00','2026-02-05 18:23:00'),
(19,'learning_outcomes','expected_graduate_elements','critical thinking and problem-solving skills;\neffective communication and collaboration;\nethical and professional practice; and,\nglobal and lifelong learning commitment.','Expected BCP Graduate Elements','2026-02-05 18:23:00','2026-02-05 18:23:00'),
(20,'policies','learners_with_disabilities','This course is committed in providing equal access and participation for all students including those with disabilities. If you have a disability that may require accommodations, please contact the OFFICE OF THE STUDENTS\' AFFAIRS and SERVICES to register in the LIST OF LEARNERS with Disabilities. Please be aware that it is your responsibility to communicate your needs and works with the instructor to ensure that appropriate accommodations can be arranged promptly.','Policy for Learners with Disabilities','2026-02-05 18:23:00','2026-02-05 18:23:00'),
(21,'policies','syllabus_flexibility','The faculty reserves the right to change or amend this syllabus as needed. Any changes to the syllabus will be communicated promptly to the VPAA through the Department Heads / Deans, if any, adjustments will be made to ensure that all students can continue to meet the course objectives. Your feedback and input are valued, and we encourage open communication to facilitate a positive and productive learning experience for all.','Syllabus Flexibility Policy','2026-02-05 18:23:01','2026-02-05 18:23:01');
